{"title_page": "Haiti/History", "text_new": "#REDIRECT [[History of Haiti]]\n\n{{R from subpage}}\n", "text_old": "#REDIRECT [[History of Haiti]]\n", "name_user": "1234qwer1234qwer4", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:R from subpage", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Haiti/History&redirect=no"}
{"title_page": "Staycation", "text_new": "{{About|a vacation where the people return home each night (or most nights)|a vacation spent in a different part of the same country|domestic tourism}} \n[[File:Woman enjoys a swimming pool.JPG|right|thumb|300px|Relaxing in a backyard swimming pool is one of the activities sometimes enjoyed during a staycation.]]\nA '''staycation''' (a [[portmanteau]] of \"stay\" and \"vacation\"), or '''holistay''' (a portmanteau of \"holiday\" and \"stay\"), is a period in which an individual or family stays home and participates in leisure activities within driving distance of their home and does not require overnight accommodations. Alternatively, and commonly in UK usage, it is a holiday spent in one's home country rather than abroad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/staycation|website=English Oxford Living Dictionaries|title=Definition of Staycation|accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref> Common activities of a staycation include use of the backyard [[swimming pool|pool]], visits to local [[park]]s and [[museum]]s, and attendance at local [[festival]]s and [[amusement parks]]. Some staycationers also like to follow a set of rules, such as setting a start and end date, planning ahead, and avoiding routine, with the goal of creating the feel of a traditional vacation.<ref name=\"amazon.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/1605506567|title=The Great American Staycation: How to Make a Vacation at Home Fun for the Whole Family|first=Matt|last=Wixon|date=18 March 2009|publisher=Adams Media|accessdate=2 August 2016|via=Amazon}}</ref>\n\nStaycations achieved  popularity in the U.S. during the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132010]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/23580960|title=Get away on vacation \u2014 at home|date=12 March 2008|publisher=|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite web|url=https://englishcountryhouse.co.uk/staycation/|title=The Ultimate Staycation Guide|publisher=|accessdate=25 September 2018}}</ref> Staycations also became a popular phenomenon in the UK in 2009 as a weak pound sterling made overseas holidays significantly more expensive.<ref>[http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/UK-News/British-Holidays-Boom-Despite-Summer-Gloom-Dull-Weather-Doesnt-Dampen-Staycation-Spirit/Article/200908215361604 \"Staycations Boom Despite Summer Gloom\"], ''[[Sky News]]'', 2009-08-16. Retrieved on 2009-09-01.</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word ''staycation'' is a [[portmanteau]] of ''stay'' (meaning stay-at-home) and ''vacation''.<ref name=Wordspy>{{cite web|url=http://www.wordspy.com/words/staycation.asp|title=staycation - Word Spy|first=Word|last=Spy|publisher=|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.consumerreports.org/home/2008/04/staycation.html|title=Buzzword: Staycation: Consumer Reports Home & Garden Blog<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> The terms \"holistay\" and \"[[daycation]]\" are also sometimes used.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\"/> The earliest reference to this term as coming from a 2003 article by Terry Massey in ''[[The Sun News]]''.<ref name=Wordspy/>\nAccording to a Connecticut travel blog, the word ''\"staycation\"'' was originally [[Coining (linguistics)|coined]] by Canadian comedian [[Brent Butt]]<ref name=Connecticut>[http://www.thisisct.net/2008/05/staycation-connecticut-style.html \"Staycation Connecticut Style\"]</ref> in the television show ''[[Corner Gas]]'', in the episode \"Mail Fraud\", which first aired October 24, 2005. The word became widely used in the United States during May 2008 as the summer travel season began with [[World oil market chronology from 2003#Mid-2008_increases|gas prices reaching record highs]], leading many people to cut back on expenses including travel.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://money.cnn.com/2008/05/07/news/economy/gas_prices_hearing/ | work=CNN | title=Congress takes on gasoline prices | date=2008-05-07 | accessdate=2010-05-24 | first=David | last=Goldman}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.consumerreports.org/home/2008/04/staycation.html|title=Buzzword: Staycation|publisher=|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref><ref>[http://www.theenvironmentalblog.org/2008/07/summer-staycation.html  Summer Staycation]</ref> Merriam-Webster cites the earliest use in the Cincinnati Enquirer, July 18, 1944. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/words-at-play/staycation-date-meaning|title=The Secret History of 'Staycation'|access-date=2017-04-19|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe term was added to the 2009 version of the [[Merriam\u2013Webster's Collegiate Dictionary]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-words-dictionary-idUSTRE5690LE20090710|title=Locavores, staycations get official in dictionary|date=10 July 2009|publisher=|accessdate=2 August 2016|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nA closely related concept and term is '''nearcation''', which is taking a vacation to a location relatively close to home.<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/id/32405982/Nearcation_Trend_Helps_Hershey_Park_Stay_Sweet - Nearcation Trend Helps Hershey Park Stay Sweet]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/travel/news/2008-08-28-staycation_N.htm|title=Vacationers travel roads closer to home to save the summer - USATODAY.com|publisher=|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> \"Nearcation\" and \"staycation\" may be used interchangeably since the travel destination may be in the same metropolitan region in which one resides and it is unclear how far away a destination needs to be until it becomes no longer a \"staycation\".\n\n[[Lake Superior State University]] added the word to its 2009 List of Banished Words. The citation noted that ''vacation'' is not synonymous with ''travel'', and thus a separate term isn't necessary to describe a vacation during which one stays at home.<ref>[https://www.lssu.edu/banished-words-list/banished-word-list-archive/ \"Lake Superior State University 2009 List of Banished Words\"], January 1, 2009.</ref>\n\n==Benefits==\nStaycations are likely to be less costly than a vacation involving traveling. There may be no lodging costs and travel expenses may be minimal. Costs may include [[transportation]] for local trips, [[dining]], and local attractions.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/24859538|title=Avoiding high gas prices with a 'staycation'|date=29 May 2008|publisher=|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref>\n\"The American Automobile Association said the average North American vacation will cost $244 per day for two people for lodging and meals.... Add some kids and airfare, and a 10-day vacation could top $8,000.\"<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nStaycations are likely to avoid some of the stress associated with travel, such as [[jet lag]], packing, long drives, or waits at [[airport]]s.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/LIVING/worklife/06/12/balance.staycation/ | work=CNN | title=Staycations: Alternative to pricey, stressful travel - CNN.com | date=2008-06-12 | accessdate=2010-05-24}}</ref>\n\nStaycations may be of economic benefit to some local businesses, who get customers from the area providing them with business. In 2008, the tourism bureaus of many U.S. cities also began promoting staycations for their residents to help replace the tourism dollars lost from a drop in out-of-town visitors.<ref name=\"amazon.com\"/>\n\n[[Environmental_impact_of_aviation|Air travel's environmental impact]] is significant. By avoiding travel, a staycation may reduce the carbon emissions associated with travel greatly.\n\n==Risks==\nAs staycationers are close to their places of employment, they may be tempted to go to work at least part of the time, and their bosses may feel their employees are available to be called into work. Staycationers also have access to their [[email]] (whether personal or business) at home as they would regularly, allowing them to be contacted, and feeling the temptation to keep up with this contact (whether business or social).<ref name=autogenerated1 /> These risks can be balanced by strictly adhering rules that make the experience feel like a real get-away, such as \"no checking email,\" or \"no watching television.\"\n\nStaycationers may spend money they had not planned as retailers and other advertisers offer \"deals\" to encourage staycationers to spend money.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/money/industries/retail/2008-05-24-staycations_N.htm | work=USA Today | title=Retailers promote 'staycation' sales | date=2008-05-23 | accessdate=2010-05-24}}</ref><ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap_travel/20080523/ap_tr_ge/travel_brief_stay_home_summer Retailers promote 'staycation' sales - Yahoo! News<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> These may include [[hotel]]s making package deals in hopes of luring planned staycationers to do some travel.<ref name=Connecticut /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc15.com/news/local/story.aspx?content_id=32089c20-8f2b-4c49-848b-57303180c369|title=abc15.com - ABC15 Arizona news in Phoenix - KNXV-TV|publisher=|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> Staycationers can also finish a stay-at-home vacation feeling unsatisfied if they allow themselves to fall into their daily monotony and include household projects, errands, and other menial tasks in their vacation at home or near home.<ref name=\"amazon.com\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Day-tripper]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q7605118|wikt=staycation|c=no|n=New_words_added_to_Webster's_dictionary|voy=Staycation|b=no|v=no|m=no|mw=no|q=no|s=no|species=no}}\n*{{Curlie|Recreation/Travel/Specialty_Travel/Budget|Budget Travel}}\n{{Tourism}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Staycation}}\n[[Category:Types of tourism]]\n[[Category:Tourist activities]]\n[[Category:Neologisms]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|a vacation where the people return home each night (or most nights)|a vacation spent in a different part of the same country|domestic tourism}} \n[[File:Woman enjoys a swimming pool.JPG|right|thumb|300px|Relaxing in a backyard swimming pool is one of the activities sometimes enjoyed during a staycation.]]\nA '''staycation''' (a [[portmanteau]] of \"stay\" and \"vacation\"), or '''holistay''' (a portmanteau of \"holiday\" and \"stay\"), is a period in which an individual or family stays home and participates in leisure activities within driving distance of their home and does not require overnight accommodations. Alternatively, and commonly in UK usage, it is a holiday spent in one's home country rather than abroad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/staycation|website=English Oxford Living Dictionaries|title=Definition of Staycation|accessdate=22 April 2019}}</ref> Common activities of a staycation include use of the backyard [[swimming pool|pool]], visits to local [[park]]s and [[museum]]s, and attendance at local [[festival]]s and [[amusement parks]]. Some staycationers also like to follow a set of rules, such as setting a start and end date, planning ahead, and avoiding routine, with the goal of creating the feel of a traditional vacation.<ref name=\"amazon.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/1605506567|title=The Great American Staycation: How to Make a Vacation at Home Fun for the Whole Family|first=Matt|last=Wixon|date=18 March 2009|publisher=Adams Media|accessdate=2 August 2016|via=Amazon}}</ref>\n\nStaycations achieved  popularity in the U.S. during the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132010]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/23580960|title=Get away on vacation \u2014 at home|date=12 March 2008|publisher=|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite web|url=https://englishcountryhouse.co.uk/staycation/|title=The Ultimate Staycation Guide|publisher=|accessdate=25 September 2018}}</ref> Staycations also became a popular phenomenon in the UK in 2009 as a weak pound made overseas holidays significantly more expensive.<ref>[http: