{"title_page": "Light-gas gun", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=May 2013}}\n[[File:Shield gun.jpg|thumb|300px|A light-gas gun at [[Rice University]]. Using hydrogen gas and powered by a [[shotgun shell]], it achieves a velocity of 7&nbsp;km/s. Used during the development of the [[Gamma-ray Large Area Space Telescope]] shield.]]\nThe '''light-gas gun''' is an apparatus for physics experiments, a highly specialized gun designed to generate very high velocities. It is usually used to study high-speed [[Ballistic impact|impact phenomena]] ([[hypervelocity]] research), such as the formation of [[impact crater]]s by [[meteorite]]s or the erosion of materials by [[micrometeoroid]]s. Some basic materials research relies on projectile impact to create high pressure: such systems are capable of forcing [[liquid hydrogen]] into [[metallic hydrogen|a metallic state]].\n\n==Operation==\n\nA light-gas gun works on the same principle as a [[Air gun#Spring-piston|spring piston airgun]]. A large-diameter piston is used to force a gaseous working fluid through a smaller-diameter barrel containing the projectile to be accelerated. This reduction in diameter acts as a lever, increasing the speed while decreasing the pressure. In an airgun, the large piston is powered by a spring or compressed air, and the working fluid is atmospheric air.\n\nIn a light-gas gun, the piston is powered by a chemical reaction (usually [[gunpowder]]), and the working fluid is a lighter gas, such as [[helium]] or [[hydrogen]] (though helium is much safer to work with, hydrogen offers the best performance [as explained below] and causes less launch-tube erosion). One addition that a light-gas gun adds to the airgun is a rupture disk, which is a disk (usually metal) of carefully calibrated thickness designed to act as a valve. When the pressure builds up to the desired level behind the disk, the disk tears open, allowing the high-pressure, light gas to pass into the barrel. This ensures that the maximum amount of energy is available when the projectile begins moving.\n[[Image:Light-gas gun.svg|thumb|450px|Diagram of a light-gas gun<br>\n'''1''' \u2014 Breech block<br>\n'''2''' \u2014 Chamber<br>\n'''3''' \u2014 Propellant charge (gunpowder)<br>\n'''4''' \u2014 Piston<br>\n'''5''' \u2014 Pump tube<br>\n'''6''' \u2014 Light gas (helium or hydrogen)<br>\n'''7''' \u2014 Rupture disk<br>\n'''8''' \u2014 High pressure coupling<br>\n'''9''' \u2014 Projectile<br>\n'''10''' \u2014 Gun barrel]]\nOne particular light-gas gun used by [[NASA]] uses a modified 40\u2013mm cannon for power. The cannon uses gunpowder to propel a plastic (usually [[High-density polyethylene|HDPE]]) piston down the cannon barrel, which is filled with high-pressure hydrogen gas. At the end of the cannon barrel is a conical section, leading down to the 5-mm barrel that fires the projectile. In this conical section is a stainless steel disk, approximately 2&nbsp;mm thick, with an \"x\" pattern scored into the surface in the middle. When the hydrogen develops sufficient pressure to burst the scored section of the disk, the hydrogen flows through the hole and accelerates the projectile to a velocity of {{convert|6|km/s|km/h|abbr=on}} in a distance of about a meter.\n\nNASA also operates light-gas guns with launch tube sizes ranging from {{convert|0.170|in}} to {{convert|1.5|in|abbr=on}} at [[Ames Research Center]]. Hazardous testing<ref name=\"WSTF\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nasa.gov/centers/wstf/laboratories/hypervelocity/ |title=Remote Hypervelocity Test Facility |date=2014-07-31 |publisher=[[NASA]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730025908/http://www.nasa.gov/centers/wstf/laboratories/hypervelocity/ |archivedate=2014-07-30 }}</ref> is conducted at [[White Sands Test Facility]]. These guns have been used in support of various missions beginning with [[Apollo program]] reentry studies in the 1960s and most recently for high-speed thermal imaging. Velocities ranging from 1&nbsp;km/s up to 8.5&nbsp;km/s can be achieved. The largest of these involves a {{convert|6.25|in|sing=on}} diameter piston weighing more than {{convert|46|lb}} to compress the hydrogen.\n\n[[Image:AEDC Range-G Launcher facility.jpg|thumb|250px|Two light-gas guns at [[Arnold Air Force Base]]'s Hypervelocity Ballistics Ranges.]]\n[[Arnold Air Force Base]]'s [[Range-G]] is the \"largest routinely operated two-stage, light-gas gun system in the United States\".<ref name=\"AEDC\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.arnold.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=13498 |title=Hypervelocity Range Facility |date=2008-12-11 |publisher=Arnold Air Force Base |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130318111929/http://www.arnold.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=13498 |archivedate=2013-03-18 }}</ref> Range-G utilizes interchangeable launch tubes ranging from a bore diameter of {{convert|3.3|in}} to {{convert|8.0|in}} with a {{convert|14.0|in|sing=on}} piston weighing up to {{convert|2300|lb}}.  Projectile velocities can reach {{convert|4.5|km/s|km/h}} for the {{convert|8.0|in|sing=on}} configuration and {{convert|7|km/s|km/h}} for the {{convert|3.3|in|sing=on}} launcher configuration.<ref name=\"AEDC\" /> The primary use of the range facilities at Arnold Air Force Base is the measurement of released kinetic energy upon projectile impact.\n\n===Design physics===\nThe muzzle velocity of an [[airgun]], [[firearm]], or light-gas gun is limited by, but not limited to, the [[speed of sound]] in the working fluid\u2014the air, burning gunpowder, or a light gas. Up to the speed of sound, thermodynamics provides a simple, approximate calculation approach: the projectile is accelerated by the pressure difference between its ends, and since such a pressure wave cannot propagate any faster than the speed of sound in the medium, thermodynamic analysis suggests that the muzzle velocity is limited to the speed of sound. However, beyond the speed of sound, the [[kinetic theory of gases]], which determines the speed of sound, provides a more detailed analysis in terms of the gas particles that comprise the working fluid. Kinetic theory indicates that the velocity of the gas particles is [[Maxwell\u2013Boltzmann distribution|Maxwell-Boltzmann distributed]], with the velocity of a large fraction of the particles exceeding the speed of sound in the gas. That fraction of the gas can continue to apply pressure to and therefore accelerate the projectile beyond the speed of sound in diminishing amounts as the projectiles speed increases.\n\nThe speed of sound in helium is about three times that in air, and in hydrogen 3.8 times that in air. The speed of sound also increases with the temperature of the fluid (but is independent of the pressure), so the heat formed by the compression of the working fluid serves to increase the maximum possible speed. Spring piston airguns increase the temperature of the air in the chamber by [[Adiabatic process|adiabatic heating]]; this raises the local speed of sound enough to overcome frictional and other efficiency losses and propel the projectile at more than the speed of sound in the ambient conditions.\n\n===Hybrid electrothermal light-gas gun===\nThe hybrid electrothermal light-gas gun works on similar principles of the standard light-gas gun, but adds an electric arc to heat the light gas to a higher temperature and pressure than the piston alone. The arc is applied in the chamber containing the light gas, raising the temperature and pressure to the point where the gas both breaks the bursting disk and ignites the propellant behind the piston, which is perforated to allow ignition. The resulting combination of electrical heating and piston compression provide higher pressures and temperatures, resulting in more power and a higher potential speed than a standard light-gas gun.<ref>{{patent|US|5429030|Hybrid electrothermal light gas gun and method}}</ref><ref>[http://google.com/patents/US5429030 Hybrid electrothermal light-gas gun and method], United States Patent 5,429,030 Tidman July 4, 1995</ref>\n\n===Impact profile===\n[[File:SDIO KEW Lexan projectile.jpg|thumb|250px|In this Kinetic Energy Weapon test, a seven-gram Lexan projectile was fired from a light-gas gun at a velocity of 23,000 feet per second (7,000 m/s; 16,000 mph) at a cast aluminum block.]]\nWhen the projectile fired by a light-gas gun impacts its target, the pressure applied depends upon the mass of the projectile and the surface area, or cross-section, over which the impact force is distributed. Because air-launched projectiles experience friction with air molecules, drag increases proportionally to increased projectile surface area, which results in slower velocities the larger the surface area of a projectile is. As such, a [[Density|dense]] and narrow projectile will apply more pressure overall than a light<!-- Re. \"light\": The intention is actually \"low density\" or \"composed of a light substance\", are there better words? --> and wide one. Looking at constant cross-sectional projectiles, researchers have recently begun to vary their projectiles' density as a function of length. Since the projectiles travel at a known velocity, changes in density as a function of length have a predictable relationship to the impact pressure applied as a function of time. With materials in a wide range of densities (from [[tungsten]] powder to [[glass microsphere]]s) applied in thin layers, carefully made projectiles can be used in constant-pressure experiments, or even controlled compression\u2013expansion\u2013compression sequences.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Combustion light-gas gun]], a high-velocity gun that uses combusted gas as propellant.\n* [[Ram accelerator]], a high-velocity gun that uses different principles to achieve similar projectile velocities.\n* [[Shock tube]], a tool used to demonstrate the properties of very high speed gases.\n* [[Voitenko compressor]], a [[shaped charge]] driven device which uses [[hydrogen]] gas to accelerate thin disks up to about 40&nbsp;km/s.\n* [[Super High Altitude Research Project]]\n* [[Space gun]]\n*Green Launch\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20020617165752/http://www-pat.llnl.gov/Organization/HDivision/Research/GasGun/GasGun.html Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory's gas gun]\n* [http://quicklaunchinc.com/ QuickLaunch, aka TekLaunch, plans to commercialize a 1 km hydrogen gun to launch fuel to low earth orbit]\n* [https://www.amotronics.de/en/measurement/sequencer.html Test Sequencer and high-speed camera controller with real-time reaction to hypervelocity events and trigger prediction capabilities]\n\n\n[[Category:Ballistics]]\n[[Category:Space guns]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=May 2013}}\n[[File:Shield gun.jpg|thumb|300px|A light-gas gun at [[Rice University]]. Using hydrogen gas and powered by a [[shotgun shell]], it achieves a velocity of 7&nbsp;km/s. Used during the development of the [[Gamma-ray Large Area Space Telescope]] shield.]]\nThe '''light-gas gun''' is an apparatus for physics experiments, a highly specialized gun designed to generate very high velocities. It is usually used to study high-speed [[Ballistic impact|impact phenomena]] ([[hypervelocity]] research), such as the formation of [[impact crater]]s by [[meteorite]]s or the erosion of materials by [[micrometeoroid]]s. Some basic materials research relies on projectile impact to create high pressure: such systems are capable of forcing [[liquid hydrogen]] into [[metallic hydrogen|a metallic state]].\n\n==Operation==\n\nA light-gas gun works on the same principle as a [[Air gun#Spring-piston|spring piston airgun]]. A large-diameter piston is used to force a gaseous working fluid through a smaller-diameter barrel containing the projectile to be accelerated. This reduction in diameter acts as a lever, increasing the speed while decreasing the pressure. In an airgun, the large piston is powered by a spring or compressed air, and the working fluid is atmospheric air.\n\nIn a light-gas gun, the piston is powered by a chemical reaction (usually [[gunpowder]]), and the working fluid is a lighter gas, such as [[helium]] or [[hydrogen]] (though helium is much safer to work with, hydrogen offers the best performance [as explained below] and causes less launch-tube erosion). One addition that a light-gas gun adds to the airgun is a rupture disk, which is a disk (usually metal) of carefully calibrated thickness designed to act as a valve. When the pressure builds up to the desired level behind the disk, the disk tears open, allowing the high-pressure, light gas to pass into the barrel. This ensures that the maximum amount of energy is available when the projectile begins moving.\n[[Image:Light-gas gun.svg|thumb|450px|Diagram of a light-gas gun<br>\n'''1''' \u2014 Breech block<br>\n'''2''' \u2014 Chamber<br>\n'''3''' \u2014 Propellant charge (gunpowder)<br>\n'''4''' \u2014 Piston<br>\n'''5''' \u2014 Pump tube<br>\n'''6''' \u2014 Light gas (helium or hydrogen)<br>\n'''7''' \u2014 Rupture disk<br>\n'''8''' \u2014 High pressure coupling<br>\n'''9''' \u2014 Projectile<br>\n'''10''' \u2014 Gun barrel]]\nOne particular light-gas gun used by [[NASA]] uses a modified 40\u2013mm cannon for power. The cannon uses gunpowder to propel a plastic (usually [[High-density polyethylene|HDPE]]) piston down the cannon barrel, which is filled with high-pressure hydrogen gas. At the end of the cannon barrel is a conical section, leading down to the 5-mm barrel that fires the projectile. In this conical section is a stainless steel disk, approximately 2&nbsp;mm thick, with an \"x\" pattern scored into the surface in the middle. When the hydrogen develops sufficient pressure to burst the scored section of the disk, the hydrogen flows through the hole and accelerates the projectile to a velocity of {{convert|6|km/s|km/h|abbr=on}} in a distance of about a meter.\n\nNASA also operates light-gas guns with launch tube sizes ranging from {{convert|0.170|in}} to {{convert|1.5|in|abbr=on}} at [[Ames Research Center]]. Hazardous testing<ref name=\"WSTF\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nasa.gov/centers/wstf/laboratories/hypervelocity/ |title=Remote Hypervelocity Test Facility |date=2014-07-31 |publisher=[[NASA]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730025908/http://www.nasa.gov/centers/wstf/laboratories/hypervelocity/ |archivedate=2014-07-30 }}</ref> is conducted at [[White Sands Test Facility]]. These guns have been used in support of various missions beginning with [[Apollo program]] reentry studies in the 1960s and most recently for high-speed thermal imaging. Velocities ranging from 1&nbsp;km/s up to 8.5&nbsp;km/s can be achieved. The largest of these involves a {{convert|6.25|in|sing=on}} diameter piston weighing more than {{convert|46|lb}} to compress the hydrogen.\n\n[[Image:AEDC Range-G Launcher facility.jpg|thumb|250px|Two light-gas guns at [[Arnold Air Force Base]]'s Hypervelocity Ballistics Ranges.]]\n[[Arnold Air Force Base]]'s [[Range-G]] is the \"largest routinely operated two-stage, light-gas gun system in the United States\".<ref name=\"AEDC\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.arnold.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=13498 |title=Hypervelocity Range Facility |date=2008-12-11 |publisher=Arnold Air Force Base |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130318111929/http://www.arnold.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=13498 |archivedate=2013-03-18 }}</ref> Range-G utilizes interchangeable launch tubes ranging from a bore diameter of {{convert|3.3|in}} to {{convert|8.0|in}} with a {{convert|14.0|in|sing=on}} piston weighing up to {{convert|2300|lb}}.  Projectile velocities can reach {{convert|4.5|km/s|km/h}} for the {{convert|8.0|in|sing=on}} configuration and {{convert|7|km/s|km/h}} for the {{convert|3.3|in|sing=on}} launcher configuration.<ref name=\"AEDC\" /> The primary use of the range facilities at Arnold Air Force Base is the measurement of released kinetic energy upon projectile impact.\n\n===Design physics===\nThe muzzle velocity of an [[airgun]], [[firearm]], or light-gas gun is limited by, but not limited to, the [[speed of sound]] in the working fluid\u2014the air, burning gunpowder, or a light gas. Up to the speed of sound, thermodynamics provides a simple, approximate calculation approach: the projectile is accelerated by the pressure difference between its ends, and since such a pressure wave cannot propagate any faster than the speed of sound in the medium, thermodynamic analysis suggests that the muzzle velocity is limited to the speed of sound. However, beyond the speed of sound, the [[kinetic theory of gases]], which determines the speed of sound, provides a more detailed analysis in terms of the gas particles that comprise the working fluid. Kinetic theory indicates that the velocity of the gas particles is [[Maxwell\u2013Boltzmann distribution|Maxwell-Boltzmann distributed]], with the velocity of a large fraction of the particles exceeding the speed of sound in the gas. That fraction of the gas can continue to apply pressure to and therefore accelerate the projectile beyond the speed of sound in diminishing amounts as the projectiles speed increases.\n\nThe speed of sound in helium is about three times that in air, and in hydrogen 3.8 times that in air. The speed of sound also increases with the temperature of the fluid (but is independent of the pressure), so the heat formed by the compression of the working fluid serves to increase the maximum possible speed. Spring piston airguns increase the temperature of the air in the chamber by adiabatic heating; this raises the local speed of sound enough to overcome frictional and other efficiency losses and propel the projectile at more than the speed of sound in the ambient conditions.\n\n===Hybrid electrothermal light-gas gun===\nThe hybrid electrothermal light-gas gun works on similar principles of the standard light-gas gun, but adds an electric arc to heat the light gas to a higher temperature and pressure than the piston alone. The arc is applied in the chamber containing the light gas, raising the temperature and pressure to the point where the gas both breaks the bursting disk and ignites the propellant behind the piston, which is perforated to allow ignition. The resulting combination of electrical heating and piston compression provide higher pressures and temperatures, resulting in more power and a higher potential speed than a standard light-gas gun.<ref>{{patent|US|5429030|Hybrid electrothermal light gas gun and method}}</ref><ref>[http://google.com/patents/US5429030 Hybrid electrothermal light-gas gun and method], United States Patent 5,429,030 Tidman July 4, 1995</ref>\n\n===Impact profile===\n[[File:SDIO KEW Lexan projectile.jpg|thumb|250px|In this Kinetic Energy Weapon test, a seven-gram Lexan projectile was fired from a light-gas gun at a velocity of 23,000 feet per second (7,000 m/s; 16,000 mph) at a cast aluminum block.]]\nWhen the projectile fired by a light-gas gun impacts its target, the pressure applied depends upon the mass of the projectile and the surface area, or cross-section, over which the impact force is distributed. Because air-launched projectiles experience friction with air molecules, drag increases proportionally to increased projectile surface area, which results in slower velocities the larger the surface area of a projectile is. As such, a [[Density|dense]] and narrow projectile will apply more pressure overall than a light<!-- Re. \"light\": The intention is actually \"low density\" or \"composed of a light substance\", are there better words? --> and wide one. Looking at constant cross-sectional projectiles, researchers have recently begun to vary their projectiles' density as a function of length. Since the projectiles travel at a known velocity, changes in density as a function of length have a predictable relationship to the impact pressure applied as a function of time. With materials in a wide range of densities (from [[tungsten]] powder to [[glass microsphere]]s) applied in thin layers, carefully made projectiles can be used in constant-pressure experiments, or even controlled compression\u2013expansion\u2013compression sequences.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Combustion light-gas gun]], a high-velocity gun that uses combusted gas as propellant.\n* [[Ram accelerator]], a high-velocity gun that uses different principles to achieve similar projectile velocities.\n* [[Shock tube]], a tool used to demonstrate the properties of very high speed gases.\n* [[Voitenko compressor]], a [[shaped charge]] driven device which uses [[hydrogen]] gas to accelerate thin disks up to about 40&nbsp;km/s.\n* [[Super High Altitude Research Project]]\n* [[Space gun]]\n*Green Launch\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20020617165752/http://www-pat.llnl.gov/Organization/HDivision/Research/GasGun/GasGun.html Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory's gas gun]\n* [http://quicklaunchinc.com/ QuickLaunch, aka TekLaunch, plans to commercialize a 1 km hydrogen gun to launch fuel to low earth orbit]\n* [https://www.amotronics.de/en/measurement/sequencer.html Test Sequencer and high-speed camera controller with real-time reaction to hypervelocity events and trigger prediction capabilities]\n\n\n[[Category:Ballistics]]\n[[Category:Space guns]]\n", "name_user": "Qi Zhengyuan 1123", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDesign physics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Light-gas_gun"}
{"title_page": "2012 Lamma Island ferry collision", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Hong Kong English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox news event\n| title                    = 2012 Lamma Island ferry collision\n| image                    = \n| image_name               = \n| image_size               =\n| caption                  =\n| date                     = {{Start date|2012|10|01|df=y}}\n| time                     = ~20:23 [[Hong Kong Time|HKT]] ([[UTC+08:00]])<ref name=\"cnn\">{{Cite news|title=At least 38 killed in Hong Kong's deadliest ferry accident in decades|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/10/02/world/asia/hong-kong-ferry-crash/index.html|accessdate=2 October 2012|publisher=CNN|date=2 October 2012|last1=Armstrong|first1=Paul|first2=Jethro|last2=Mullen}}</ref>\n| place                    = Half a mile off [[Yung Shue Wan]], [[Lamma Island]], Hong Kong\n| coordinates              = {{Coord|22|14|8|N|114|6|14|E|region:HK_type:event|display=inline,title}}\n| also known as            =\n| cause                    = Collision\n| participants             =\n| outcome                  = Sinking of ''Lamma IV'', ''Sea Smooth'' damaged\n| reported injuries        = 92<ref name=\"Apple Daily 20130412\">{{Cite news|title=\u5169\u6d89\u6848\u8239\u9577\u3000\u5171\u88ab\u63a778\u9805\u8aa4\u6bba\u7f6a|url=http://hk.apple.nextmedia.com/news/art/20130412/18225531|accessdate=23 June 2013|publisher=Apple Daily|date=12 April 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Asia Pacific Daily 20130411\">{{Cite news|title=\u9999\u6e2f\u5357\u4e2b\u5cf6\u649e\u8239\u4e8b\u6545\u5169\u4eba\u88ab\u63a7\u8aa4\u6bba |url=http://www.apdnews.com/news/24310.html |accessdate=23 June 2013 |publisher=Asia Pacific Daily |date=11 April 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6I4ePTgNH?url=http://www.apdnews.com/news/24310.html |archivedate=13 July 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n| reported death(s)        = 39<ref name=\"South China Morning Post 20130111\">{{Cite news|title=List of the 39 deceased in the Lamma ferry disaster |url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/1125731/list-39-deceased-lamma-ferry-disaster |accessdate=23 June 2013 |publisher=South China Morning Post |date=11 January 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6I4eNfyXy?url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/1125731/list-39-deceased-lamma-ferry-disaster |archivedate=13 July 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n| reported missing         =\n| reported property damage =\n| burial                   =\n| inquiries                =\n| inquest                  =\n| coroner                  =\n| suspects                 =\n| charges                  =\n| verdict                  =\n| convictions              =\n| publication bans         =\n| litigation               =\n| awards                   =\n| url                      =\n| website                  = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| notes                    =\n}}\n<!-- Per MOS:BOLDTITLE and WP:SBE, neither the article's title nor related text appears in bold. -->On 1 October 2012, at approximately 20:23 [[Hong Kong Time|HKT]], the passenger [[ferries]] ''Sea Smooth'' and ''Lamma IV'' collided off [[Yung Shue Wan]], [[Lamma Island]], Hong Kong.<ref name=\"cnn\"/> This occurred on the [[National Day of the People's Republic of China]], and one of the ships was headed for the commemorative firework display, scheduled to take place half an hour later. With 39 killed<ref name=\"South China Morning Post 20130111\"/> and 92 injured,<ref name=\"Apple Daily 20130412\"/><ref name=\"Asia Pacific Daily 20130411\"/> the incident was the deadliest maritime disaster in Hong Kong since 1971.<ref name=\"cnn\"/> \n\nOn 14 February 2015, ''Sea Smooth''\u2032s captain Lai Sai-ming was convicted of 39 counts of manslaughter over the deaths, while ''Lamma IV''\u2032s captain Chow Chi-wai was acquitted of the same charges by the High Court. Both men were found guilty of endangering the safety of others at sea.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sea Smooth skipper convicted of manslaughter as Lamma ferry captain cleared of same charges|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/1710671/lamma-fery-verdicts-skipper-acquitted-first-count-manslaughter|accessdate=14 February 2015|publisher=South China Morning Post|date=14 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hong Kong 2012 ferry disaster: Captain convicted|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-31468706|accessdate=14 February 2015|publisher=BBC News|date=14 February 2015}}</ref> On 16 February, Lai and Chow were sentenced to eight years' and nine months' imprisonment respectively.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://rthk.hk/rthk/news/englishnews/news.htm?hightlight&20150216&56&1077647|title = Lamma ferry captain jailed for eight years|last = |first = |date = 16 February 2015|work = RTHK|access-date = 16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n[[File:2012 Lamma Island ferry collision - Sea Smooth-01.JPG|thumb|left|''Sea Smooth'' after the collision, showing damage on the left bow]]\nThe accident involved a [[Hong Kong & Kowloon Ferry]]-operated passenger ferry, ''Sea Smooth'' (\u6d77\u6cf0\u865f), and a [[Hongkong Electric Company]]-owned vessel, ''Lamma IV'' (\u5357\u4e2b\u56db\u865f), with 121 passengers and 3 crew members on board. The passenger ferry was travelling from [[Central, Hong Kong|Central]] to [[Yung Shue Wan]], while the Hongkong Electric Company vessel was travelling from Lamma Island to Central. Passengers on ''Lamma IV'' were on a one-day tour organised by the company, and were headed to Central for the fireworks display commemorating the [[National Day of the PRC]] following a tour of the [[Lamma Power Station]].<ref name=\"xinhua\">{{Cite news|title=Death toll of HK ship collision rises to 38; six crew detained|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/china/2012-10/02/c_131885711.htm|accessdate=2 October 2012|publisher=Xinhua|date=2 October 2012}}</ref> Participants of the tour mostly joined as families, and as a result there were a number of children among the passengers.\n\n==Accident==\nAt approximately 20:20, ''Sea Smooth'' crashed into ''Lamma IV'' on the [[port and starboard|port]] side.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Cause of accident failure to yield (Chinese)|url=http://news.cn.yahoo.com/ypen/20121004/1344449.html|access-date=4 October 2012|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130106004659/http://news.cn.yahoo.com/ypen/20121004/1344449.html|archive-date=6 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The bow of ''Sea Smooth'' hit the stern of ''Lamma IV'', rupturing the ship's two watertight compartments and thereby allowing them to quickly fill with water.<ref name=\"arrest\"/><ref>{{Cite news|title=Why the Lamma IV sank so quickly|newspaper=South China Morning Post|date=3 October 2012|author=Wong, Olga|author2=Lee, Ada}}</ref> The ship soon capsized with the rear sinking into the sea. The vessel reportedly went down so quickly that more than 100 passengers were thrown into the water unprotected despite the abundance of life-vests on board. The ferry left the scene after the accident and continued on to Yung Shue Wan pier. The front of ''Sea Smooth'' was damaged and its captain was also sent to the local clinic after the accident, along with several passengers, for injuries.\n[[File:LammaIV-01.JPG|thumb|The crippled ''Lamma IV'', on a beach at Nga Kau Wan on the Lamma Island after the accident.]]\n\n==Casualties==\nA total of 39 people were killed in the accident,<ref name=\"South China Morning Post 20130111\"/> all from ''Lamma IV'', 30 of whom were pronounced dead at the scene, while eight others were certified dead upon arrival at hospitals<ref>{{cite press release |title=Vessel collision incident near Lamma Island (3)|url=http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201210/02/P201210020517.htm|accessdate=5 October 2012|publisher=Hong Kong Government |date=2 October 2012}}</ref> and one died in hospital on 5 October.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Ferry disaster death toll rises to 39|url=http://rthk.hk/rthk/news/englishnews/news.htm?hightlight&20121005&56&874323.|accessdate=5 October 2012|publisher=RTHK|date=5 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n92 people on both vessels were injured,<ref name=\"Apple Daily 20130412\"/><ref name=\"Asia Pacific Daily 20130411\"/> four of whom sustained severe injures. While the Hongkong Electric company claimed 124 people were on ''Lamma IV'', police suspected that there might have been more on board as company employees were allowed to invite their own friends.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=zh:\u5169\u8239\u9577\u7591\u9e75\u83bd\u5bb338\u547d|trans-title=Careless driving by 2 captains took 38 lives |language=Chinese|url=http://hk.news.yahoo.com/%E5%85%A9%E8%88%B9%E9%95%B7%E7%96%91%E9%B9%B5%E8%8E%BD%E5%AE%B338%E5%91%BD-220814168.html|accessdate=3 October 2012|work=Singtao Daily|date=3 October 2012}}</ref> As a result, the number of people missing remained unknown.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{Cite news|title=Hong Kong fatal boat collision leads to arrests|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-19797588|accessdate=2 October 2012|publisher=BBC News|date=2 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=7 crew arrested in deadly Hong Kong boat collision|url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/7-crew-arrested-in-deadly-Hong-Kong-boat-collision-3911400.php|accessdate=3 October 2012|work=San Francisco Chronicle|date=2 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Rescue efforts==\nAn air-and-sea rescue effort was initiated. The [[Fire Services Department (Hong Kong)|Fire Services Department]] deployed 10 launches, including a diving support vessel and mobilised 350 officers, including fire and [[Fire Services Department#Ambulance services|ambulance personnel]] and more than 60 ambulances (including ambulances from [[Hong Kong St. John Ambulance|St John Ambulance]] and [[Auxiliary Medical Service]]).<ref>{{Cite news|title=(translated from Chinese) 1000 rescuers from across departments|url=http://news.mingpao.com/20121003/gan3_image1.htm|accessdate=3 October 2012|work=Ming Pao|date=3 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=(initial report) Vessel collision incident near Lamma Island|url=http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201210/02/P201210020107.htm|\naccessdate=3 October 2012|publisher=Hong Kong Government |date=2 October 2012}}</ref> The injured were taken to five hospitals around Hong Kong. The Hong Kong government had requested help from the nearby [[Guangdong]] province to aid in search-and-rescue, but external resources were not deployed at all as domestic resources were seen as adequate by the rescue forces.{{Citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n\n==Investigation==\nInitial speculations on the cause of the accident included speeding and overloading. However, witnesses on ''Lamma IV'' claimed that the ship was cruising at a steady speed. Overloading was also ruled out as the vessel had a capacity of 200 passengers. [[Andy Tsang]], the [[Commissioner of Police (Hong Kong)|Commissioner of Police]], stated that seven crew members of the vessels were arrested the day after the accident, for \"endangering people's lives at sea\".<ref name=\"arrest\">{{Cite news|title=Seven ferry crew arrested|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|date=3 October 2012|author=Lo, Clifford|author2=Cheung, Simpson|author3=Wong, Olga|author4=Lee, Ada|author5=Wei, Lo}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref>{{Cite news|title=Arrests over deadly Hong Kong ferry collision|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia-pacific/2012/10/20121020201019674.html|accessdate=2 October 2012|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=2 October 2012}}</ref> A commission of inquiry was formed to investigate the cause of the accident.<ref name=\"arrest\"/>\n\nThe Commission of Inquiry into the Collision of Vessels near Lamma Island on 1 October 2012 was appointed by the Chief Executive in Council to inquire into the facts and circumstances leading to and surrounding the collision. The Commission of Inquiry submitted its report to the Chief Executive on 19 April 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Commission of Inquiry into the Collision of Vessels near Lamma Island on 1 October 2012|url=http://www.coi-lamma.gov.hk/eng/index.html|accessdate=30 April 2013}}</ref> The full report is available on the website of the Commission.<ref>{{cite web|title=Report of the Commission of Inquiry into the Collision of Vessels near Lamma Island on 1 October 2012|url=http://www.legco.gov.hk/yr12-13/english/panels/edev/papers/edev0527-rpt20130430-e.pdf|publisher=Commission of Inquiry into the Collision of Vessels near Lamma Island on 1 October 2012|date=April 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Hong Kong Police crime statistics for 2013 included the 39 killed as part of the city's overall murder rate for the year in the annual [[Crime in Hong Kong]] reports.<ref>{{cite web|title=Murders grip the attention in Hong Kong|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/1630194/murders-grip-attention-hong-kong-one-worlds-safest-cities?page=all|website=South China Morning Post|accessdate=1 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n\n===Hongkong Electric===\n[[File:Hong Kong mourns Lamma ferry victims 01.jpg|thumb|Chief Executive Leung and other government officials observe three minutes of silence outside the Central Government Complex in Tamar, while the flags of Hong Kong and China are flown at half-mast]]\n[[File:People signed the condolence book at Lamma Island pier in Central.jpg|thumb|Mourners signed the condolence book at the Central ferry pier for ferries to Lamma Island.]]\nOn 2 October, the flags of [[Cheung Kong Group]] companies were all flown at half-mast at the [[Cheung Kong Center]], headquarters of Hongkong Electric's parent company.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Chen|first=Te-Ping|title=Dozens Die as Two Hong Kong Boats Crash|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390444592404578030472606858726?mod=googlenews_wsj|accessdate=2 October 2012|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=2 October 2012}}</ref> Hongkong Electric confirmed that seven of those who died were staff of the Company. HK Electric announced that families of each of the deceased would receive a HK$200,000 emergency relief.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Press Release [2 October 2012\u30009:00pm<nowiki>]</nowiki>|url=http://www.hkelectric.com/web/MediaCentre/PressRelease/Year2012/2-02102012_en.htm|accessdate=2 October 2012|publisher=Hongkong Electric|date=3 October 2012 }}</ref> Li Ka Shing, who controls HK Electric, immediately returned to the city the next morning. It was announced that the Li Ka Shing Foundation would set aside a total of HK$30 million for victims and their families that would be in addition to the emergency relief already offered by HKE to the families of the deceased.<ref>Chan, Candy (3 October 2012). [http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?pp_cat=30&art_id=126951&sid=37801900&con_type=1&d_str=20121003&isSearch=1&sear_year=2012 \"Funds for victims as Li rushes back\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130107185537/http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?pp_cat=30&art_id=126951&sid=37801900&con_type=1&d_str=20121003&isSearch=1&sear_year=2012 |date=7 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Hong Kong Government===\nThree [[National day of mourning|days of mourning]] were declared by Chief Executive [[Leung Chun-ying]], starting on 4 October, during which the [[flag of Hong Kong]] was flown at half-mast on all government buildings. On 4 October, Leung, along with other government officials, observed [[Moment of silence|three minutes of silence]] outside the [[Central Government Complex, Tamar|Central Government Offices]] at 12:00. Schools and other public offices also observed a moment of silence.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Hong Kong mourns victims of Lamma Island boat collision|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-19824735|accessdate=4 October 2012|publisher=BBC News|date=4 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"xinhua\"/> Condolence points were set up in each of the 18 districts during the mourning period.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Condolence points set up to mourn victims|url=http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201210/02/P201210020573.htm|accessdate=3 October 2012|publisher=Hong Kong Government|date=3 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe government cancelled the 2013 National Day Fireworks as a result of the incident.\n\n===Others===\nOn 2 October, British Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] sent Chief Executive Leung his condolences.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.number10.gov.uk/news/pm-sends-condolences-to-chief-executive-of-hong-kong/|title=PM sends condolences to Chief Executive of Hong Kong |publisher=Office of the Prime Minister of the United Kingdom}}</ref> [[Catherine Ashton]], [[High Representative of the Union for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy|High Representative for Foreign Affairs]] of the [[European Union]], also expressed her sadness and sent her condolences through a spokesman.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://hk.news.yahoo.com/%E6%AD%90%E7%9B%9F%E5%93%80%E6%82%BC%E9%81%87%E9%9B%A3%E8%80%85-042800080.html|title=Condolences from the EU}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nThe decision by the captain of ''Sea Smooth'' to leave the scene sparked a heated debate, [[Captain goes down with the ship|namely whether saving oneself, or risking oneself for the others has a high priority.]]<ref>{{Cite news|title=Should you save yourself or others in a collision: a legal and moral debate (Chinese)|url=http://hk.news.yahoo.com/%E6%92%9E%E8%88%B9%E6%95%91%E4%BA%BA%E6%88%96%E5%85%88%E8%87%AA%E6%95%91-%E6%B3%95%E5%BE%8B%E9%81%93%E5%BE%B7%E5%85%B7%E7%88%AD%E8%AD%B0-224632742.html|accessdate=5 October 2012|date=3 October 2012}}</ref> At first, reports stated that the captain continued on to the pier out of passenger request and out of fear that ''Sea Smooth'' herself might sink, but later reports also claimed that some passengers urged the captain to stop.<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u6e21\u8f2a\u5ba2\u547c\u505c\u8239 \u8239\u9577\u4e0d\u7406 \u6536\u96c6\u6551\u751f\u8863 \u64ec\u62cb\u6d77\u6551\u4eba(Chinese)|url=http://hk.news.yahoo.com/%E6%B8%A1%E8%BC%AA%E5%AE%A2%E5%91%BC%E5%81%9C%E8%88%B9-%E8%88%B9%E9%95%B7%E4%B8%8D%E7%90%86-%E6%94%B6%E9%9B%86%E6%95%91%E7%94%9F%E8%A1%A3-%E6%93%AC%E6%8B%8B%E6%B5%B7%E6%95%91%E4%BA%BA-212119092.html|accessdate=5 October 2012|date=3 October 2012}}</ref> In the few days following the accident, the captain had remained emotionally unstable even after being discharged from the hospital.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Captain of Sea Smooth discharged, emotionally unstable (Chinese)|url=http://hk.news.yahoo.com/%E6%B5%B7%E6%B3%B0%E8%88%B9%E9%95%B7%E5%87%BA%E9%99%A2-%E9%8C%84%E5%8F%A3%E4%BE%9B%E6%83%85%E7%B7%92%E6%9C%AA%E7%A9%A9-223000610.html|accessdate=5 October 2012|date=3 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter he was informed of the accident, Chief Executive Leung Chun-ying immediately set out to the scene to oversee the rescue efforts.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://orientaldaily.on.cc/cnt/news/20121002/00176_010.html|title=Leung overseeing rescue on scene|accessdate=5 October 2012|date=2 October 2012|work=Oriental Daily}}</ref> Some media{{which|date=October 2012}} suggested it was a \"political show\", and said that his presence might have actually slowed down the rescue.\n\nLeung was also criticised{{by whom|date=October 2012}} for his decision to ask for help from Mainland China through the [[Liaison Office of the Central People's Government in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region|Liaison Office of the Central People's Government]], despite the abundance of manpower and resources already in Hong Kong. Many{{who|date=October 2012}} saw this as increased influence and reliance on the [[Government of the People's Republic of China|Central government]], a change from the previous [[Donald Tsang|Tsang]] administration.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Looking at Hong Kong-Chinese relationship from disaster|url=http://www.vjmedia.com.hk/articles/2012/10/02/20887|accessdate=5 October 2012|date=2 October 2012}}</ref> Also, despite Leung's clarification that no ship from Mainland China had been deployed in the rescue, on 3 October Mainland China's [[China News Service]] reported that \"95 people had been rescued by the professional Chinese rescue fleet\".<ref>{{Cite news|title=Ferry crash response revives distrust between Hong Kong and mainland China|url=http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/regions/asia-pacific/china/121003/ferry-crash-response-revives-distrust-between-hong-k|accessdate=5 October 2012|author=Carlson, Benjamin |work=Global Post |date=3 October 2012}}</ref> The news agency later deleted the number rescued, but the report had not been fully withdrawn and the claim remained that Chinese ships had helped in the rescue.<ref>{{Cite news|title=95 rescued in a dubious claim by Chinese News Service|url=http://hk.apple.nextmedia.com/news/art/20121003/18031122|accessdate=5 October 2012|date=3 October 2012 |work=Apple Daily}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.coi-lamma.gov.hk/eng/index.html Commission of Inquiry into the Collision of Vessels near Lamma Island on 1 October 2012]\n*[[Marine Department (Hong Kong)|Marine Department]]\n**\"[http://www.mardep.gov.hk/en/news/pdf/tf_pn20160831.pdf Report of a Public Inquiry, Convened Pursuant to s 17, Merchant Shipping (Local Vessels) Ordinance Cap 548.]\" \n**\"[http://www.mardep.gov.hk/en/aboutus/pdf/lvac_jsc_p1201.pdf Paper No. 1/2012 LOCAL VESSELS ADVISORY COMMITTEE  Meeting of Joint Sub-committee on Class I and Class IV Vessels Traffic control and safety measures for fireworks displays and other major events ].\"\n\n{{2012 shipwrecks}}\n\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 2012]]\n[[Category:2012 in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Ships sunk in collisions]]\n[[Category:Ferries]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of Hong Kong]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use Hong Kong English|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox news event\n| title                    = 2012 Lamma Island ferry collision\n| image                    = \n| image_name               = \n| image_size               =\n| caption                  =\n| date                     = {{Start date|2012|10|01|df=y}}\n| time                     = ~20:23 [[Hong Kong Time|HKT]] ([[UTC+08:00]])<ref name=\"cnn\">{{Cite news|title=At least 38 killed in Hong Kong's deadliest ferry accident in decades|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/10/02/world/asia/hong-kong-ferry-crash/index.html|accessdate=2 October 2012|publisher=CNN|date=2 October 2012|last1=Armstrong|first1=Paul|first2=Jethro|last2=Mullen}}</ref>\n| place                    = Half a mile off [[Yung Shue Wan]], [[Lamma Island]], Hong Kong\n| coordinates              = {{Coord|22|14|8|N|114|6|14|E|region:HK_type:event|display=inline,title}}\n| also known as            =\n| cause                    = Collision\n| participants             =\n| outcome                  = Sinking of ''Lamma IV'', ''Sea Smooth'' damaged\n| reported injuries        = 92<ref name=\"Apple Daily 20130412\">{{Cite news|title=\u5169\u6d89\u6848\u8239\u9577\u3000\u5171\u88ab\u63a778\u9805\u8aa4\u6bba\u7f6a|url=http://hk.apple.nextmedia.com/news/art/20130412/18225531|accessdate=23 June 2013|publisher=Apple Daily|date=12 April 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Asia Pacific Daily 20130411\">{{Cite news|title=\u9999\u6e2f\u5357\u4e2b\u5cf6\u649e\u8239\u4e8b\u6545\u5169\u4eba\u88ab\u63a7\u8aa4\u6bba |url=http://www.apdnews.com/news/24310.html |accessdate=23 June 2013 |publisher=Asia Pacific Daily |date=11 April 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6I4ePTgNH?url=http://www.apdnews.com/news/24310.html |archivedate=13 July 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n| reported death(s)        = 39<ref name=\"South China Morning Post 20130111\">{{Cite news|title=List of the 39 deceased in the Lamma ferry disaster |url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/1125731/list-39-deceased-lamma-ferry-disaster |accessdate=23 June 2013 |publisher=South China Morning Post |date=11 January 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6I4eNfyXy?url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/1125731/list-39-deceased-lamma-ferry-disaster |archivedate=13 July 2013 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref>\n| reported missing         =\n| reported property damage =\n| burial                   =\n| inquiries                =\n| inquest                  =\n| coroner                  =\n| suspects                 =\n| charges                  =\n| verdict                  =\n| convictions              =\n| publication bans         =\n| litigation               =\n| awards                   =\n| url                      =\n| website                  = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| notes                    =\n}}\n<!-- Per MOS:BOLDTITLE and WP:SBE, neither the article's title nor related text appears in bold. -->On 1 October 2012, at approximately 20:23 [[Hong Kong Time|HKT]], the passenger [[ferries]] ''Sea Smooth'' and ''Lamma IV'' collided off [[Yung Shue Wan]], [[Lamma Island]], Hong Kong.<ref name=\"cnn\"/> This occurred on the [[National Day of the People's Republic of China]], and one of the ships was headed for the commemorative firework display, scheduled to take place half an hour later. With 39 killed<ref name=\"South China Morning Post 20130111\"/> and 92 injured,<ref name=\"Apple Daily 20130412\"/><ref name=\"Asia Pacific Daily 20130411\"/> the incident was the deadliest maritime disaster in Hong Kong since 1971.<ref name=\"cnn\"/> \n\nOn 14 February 2015, ''Sea Smooth''\u2032s captain Lai Sai-ming was convicted of 39 counts of manslaughter over the deaths, while ''Lamma IV''\u2032s captain Chow Chi-wai was acquitted of the same charges by the High Court. Both men were found guilty of endangering the safety of others at sea.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sea Smooth skipper convicted of manslaughter as Lamma ferry captain cleared of same charges|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/1710671/lamma-fery-verdicts-skipper-acquitted-first-count-manslaughter|accessdate=14 February 2015|publisher=South China Morning Post|date=14 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hong Kong 2012 ferry disaster: Captain convicted|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-31468706|accessdate=14 February 2015|publisher=BBC News|date=14 February 2015}}</ref> On 16 February, Lai and Chow were sentenced to eight years' and nine months' imprisonment respectively.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://rthk.hk/rthk/news/englishnews/news.htm?hightlight&20150216&56&1077647|title = Lamma ferry captain jailed for eight years|last = |first = |date = 16 February 2015|work = RTHK|access-date = 16 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n[[File:2012 Lamma Island ferry collision - Sea Smooth-01.JPG|thumb|left|''Sea Smooth'' after the collision, showing damage on the left bow]]\nThe accident involved a [[Hong Kong & Kowloon Ferry]]-operated passenger ferry, ''Sea Smooth'' (\u6d77\u6cf0\u865f), and a [[Hongkong Electric Company]]-owned vessel, ''Lamma IV'' (\u5357\u4e2b\u56db\u865f), with 121 passengers and 3 crew members on board. The passenger ferry was travelling from [[Central, Hong Kong|Central]] to [[Yung Shue Wan]], while the Hongkong Electric Company vessel was travelling from Lamma Island to Central. Passengers on ''Lamma IV'' were on a one-day tour organised by the company, and were headed to Central for the fireworks display commemorating the [[National Day of the PRC]] following a tour of the [[Lamma Power Station]].<ref name=\"xinhua\">{{Cite news|title=Death toll of HK ship collision rises to 38; six crew detained|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/china/2012-10/02/c_131885711.htm|accessdate=2 October 2012|publisher=Xinhua|date=2 October 2012}}</ref> Participants of the tour mostly joined as families, and as a result there were a number of children among the passengers.\n\n==Accident==\nAt approximately 20:20, ''Sea Smooth'' crashed into ''Lamma IV'' on the [[port and starboard|port]] side.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Cause of accident failure to yield (Chinese)|url=http://news.cn.yahoo.com/ypen/20121004/1344449.html|access-date=4 October 2012|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130106004659/http://news.cn.yahoo.com/ypen/20121004/1344449.html|archive-date=6 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The bow of ''Sea Smooth'' hit the stern of ''Lamma IV'', rupturing the ship's two watertight compartments and thereby allowing them to quickly fill with water.<ref name=\"arrest\"/><ref>{{Cite news|title=Why the Lamma IV sank so quickly|newspaper=South China Morning Post|date=3 October 2012|author=Wong, Olga|author2=Lee, Ada}}</ref> The ship soon capsized with the rear sinking into the sea. The vessel reportedly went down so quickly that more than 100 passengers were thrown into the water unprotected despite the abundance of life-vests on board. The ferry left the scene after the accident and continued on to Yung Shue Wan pier. The front of ''Sea Smooth'' was damaged and its captain was also sent to the local clinic after the accident, along with several passengers, for injuries.\n[[File:LammaIV-01.JPG|thumb|The crippled ''Lamma IV'', on a beach at Nga Kau Wan on the Lamma Island after the accident.]]\n\n==Casualties==\nA total of 39 people were killed in the accident,<ref name=\"South China Morning Post 20130111\"/> all from ''Lamma IV'', 30 of whom were pronounced dead at the scene, while eight others were certified dead upon arrival at hospitals<ref>{{cite press release |title=Vessel collision incident near Lamma Island (3)|url=http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201210/02/P201210020517.htm|accessdate=5 October 2012|publisher=Hong Kong Government |date=2 October 2012}}</ref> and one died in hospital on 5 October.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Ferry disaster death toll rises to 39|url=http://rthk.hk/rthk/news/englishnews/news.htm?hightlight&20121005&56&874323.|accessdate=5 October 2012|publisher=RTHK|date=5 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n92 people on both vessels were injured,<ref name=\"Apple Daily 20130412\"/><ref name=\"Asia Pacific Daily 20130411\"/> four of whom sustained severe injures. While the Hongkong Electric company claimed 124 people were on ''Lamma IV'', police suspected that there might have been more on board as company employees were allowed to invite their own friends.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=zh:\u5169\u8239\u9577\u7591\u9e75\u83bd\u5bb338\u547d|trans-title=Careless driving by 2 captains took 38 lives |language=Chinese|url=http://hk.news.yahoo.com/%E5%85%A9%E8%88%B9%E9%95%B7%E7%96%91%E9%B9%B5%E8%8E%BD%E5%AE%B338%E5%91%BD-220814168.html|accessdate=3 October 2012|work=Singtao Daily|date=3 October 2012}}</ref> As a result, the number of people missing remained unknown.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{Cite news|title=Hong Kong fatal boat collision leads to arrests|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-19797588|accessdate=2 October 2012|publisher=BBC News|date=2 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=7 crew arrested in deadly Hong Kong boat collision|url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/7-crew-arrested-in-deadly-Hong-Kong-boat-collision-3911400.php|accessdate=3 October 2012|work=San Francisco Chronicle|date=2 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Rescue efforts==\nAn air-and-sea rescue effort was initiated. The [[Fire Services Department (Hong Kong)|Fire Services Department]] deployed 10 launches, including a diving support vessel and mobilised 350 officers, including fire and [[Fire Services Department#Ambulance services|ambulance personnel]] and more than 60 ambulances (including ambulances from [[Hong Kong St. John Ambulance|St John Ambulance]] and [[Auxiliary Medical Service]]).<ref>{{Cite news|title=(translated from Chinese) 1000 rescuers from across departments|url=http://news.mingpao.com/20121003/gan3_image1.htm|accessdate=3 October 2012|work=Ming Pao|date=3 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=(initial report) Vessel collision incident near Lamma Island|url=http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201210/02/P201210020107.htm|\naccessdate=3 October 2012|publisher=Hong Kong Government |date=2 October 2012}}</ref> The injured were taken to five hospitals around Hong Kong. The Hong Kong government had requested help from the nearby [[Guangdong]] province to aid in search-and-rescue, but external resources were not deployed at all as domestic resources were seen as adequate by the rescue forces.{{Citation needed|date=October 2012}}\n\n==Investigation==\nInitial speculations on the cause of the accident included speeding and overloading. However, witnesses on ''Lamma IV'' claimed that the ship was cruising at a steady speed. Overloading was also ruled out as the vessel had a capacity of 200 passengers. [[Andy Tsang]], the [[Commissioner of Police (Hong Kong)|Commissioner of Police]], stated that seven crew members of the vessels were arrested the day after the accident, for \"endangering people's lives at sea\".<ref name=\"arrest\">{{Cite news|title=Seven ferry crew arrested|newspaper=[[South China Morning Post]]|date=3 October 2012|author=Lo, Clifford|author2=Cheung, Simpson|author3=Wong, Olga|author4=Lee, Ada|author5=Wei, Lo}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC\"/><ref>{{Cite news|title=Arrests over deadly Hong Kong ferry collision|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia-pacific/2012/10/20121020201019674.html|accessdate=2 October 2012|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=2 October 2012}}</ref> A commission of inquiry was formed to investigate the cause of the accident.<ref name=\"arrest\"/>\n\nThe Commission of Inquiry into the Collision of Vessels near Lamma Island on 1 October 2012 was appointed by the Chief Executive in Council to inquire into the facts and circumstances leading to and surrounding the collision. The Commission of Inquiry submitted its report to the Chief Executive on 19 April 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Commission of Inquiry into the Collision of Vessels near Lamma Island on 1 October 2012|url=http://www.coi-lamma.gov.hk/eng/index.html|accessdate=30 April 2013}}</ref> The full report is available on the website of the Commission.<ref>{{cite web|title=Report of the Commission of Inquiry into the Collision of Vessels near Lamma Island on 1 October 2012|url=http://www.legco.gov.hk/yr12-13/english/panels/edev/papers/edev0527-rpt20130430-e.pdf|publisher=Commission of Inquiry into the Collision of Vessels near Lamma Island on 1 October 2012|date=April 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Hong Kong Police crime statistics for 2013 included the 39 killed as part of the city's overall murder rate for the year in the annual [[Crime in Hong Kong]] reports.<ref>{{cite web|title=Murders grip the attention in Hong Kong|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/1630194/murders-grip-attention-hong-kong-one-worlds-safest-cities?page=all|website=South China Morning Post|accessdate=1 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n\n===Hongkong Electric===\n[[File:Hong Kong mourns Lamma ferry victims 01.jpg|thumb|Chief Executive Leung and other government officials observe three minutes of silence outside the Central Government Complex in Tamar, while the flags of Hong Kong and China are flown at half-mast]]\n[[File:People signed the condolence book at Lamma Island pier in Central.jpg|thumb|Mourners signed the condolence book at the Central ferry pier for ferries to Lamma Island.]]\nOn 2 October, the flags of [[Cheung Kong Group]] companies were all flown at half-mast at the [[Cheung Kong Center]], headquarters of Hongkong Electric's parent company.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Chen|first=Te-Ping|title=Dozens Die as Two Hong Kong Boats Crash|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390444592404578030472606858726?mod=googlenews_wsj|accessdate=2 October 2012|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=2 October 2012}}</ref> Hongkong Electric confirmed that seven of those who died were staff of the Company. HK Electric announced that families of each of the deceased would receive a HK$200,000 emergency relief.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Press Release [2 October 2012\u30009:00pm<nowiki>]</nowiki>|url=http://www.hkelectric.com/web/MediaCentre/PressRelease/Year2012/2-02102012_en.htm|accessdate=2 October 2012|publisher=Hongkong Electric|date=3 October 2012 }}</ref> Li Ka Shing, who controls HK Electric, immediately returned to the city the next morning. It was announced that the Li Ka Shing Foundation would set aside a total of HK$30 million for victims and their families that would be in addition to the emergency relief already offered by HKE to the families of the deceased.<ref>Chan, Candy (3 October 2012). [http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?pp_cat=30&art_id=126951&sid=37801900&con_type=1&d_str=20121003&isSearch=1&sear_year=2012 \"Funds for victims as Li rushes back\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130107185537/http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?pp_cat=30&art_id=126951&sid=37801900&con_type=1&d_str=20121003&isSearch=1&sear_year=2012 |date=7 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Hong Kong Government===\nThree [[National day of mourning|days of mourning]] were declared by Chief Executive [[Leung Chun-ying]], starting on 4 October, during which the [[flag of Hong Kong]] was flown at half-mast on all government buildings. On 4 October, Leung, along with other government officials, observed [[Moment of silence|three minutes of silence]] outside the [[Central Government Complex, Tamar|Central Government Offices]] at 12:00. Schools and other public offices also observed a moment of silence.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Hong Kong mourns victims of Lamma Island boat collision|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-19824735|accessdate=4 October 2012|publisher=BBC News|date=4 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"xinhua\"/> Condolence points were set up in each of the 18 districts during the mourning period.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Condolence points set up to mourn victims|url=http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201210/02/P201210020573.htm|accessdate=3 October 2012|publisher=Hong Kong Government|date=3 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe government cancelled the 2013 National Day Fireworks as a result of the incident.\n\n===Others===\nOn 2 October, British Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] sent Chief Executive Leung his condolences.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.number10.gov.uk/news/pm-sends-condolences-to-chief-executive-of-hong-kong/|title=PM sends condolences to Chief Executive of Hong Kong |publisher=Office of the Prime Minister of the United Kingdom}}</ref> [[Catherine Ashton]], [[High Representative of the Union for Foreign Affairs and Security Policy|High Representative for Foreign Affairs]] of the [[European Union]], also expressed her sadness and sent her condolences through a spokesman.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://hk.news.yahoo.com/%E6%AD%90%E7%9B%9F%E5%93%80%E6%82%BC%E9%81%87%E9%9B%A3%E8%80%85-042800080.html|title=Condolences from the EU}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nThe decision by the captain of ''Sea Smooth'' to leave the scene sparked a heated debate, [[Captain goes down with the ship|namely whether saving oneself, or risking oneself for the others has a high priority.]]<ref>{{Cite news|title=Should you save yourself or others in a collision: a legal and moral debate (Chinese)|url=http://hk.news.yahoo.com/%E6%92%9E%E8%88%B9%E6%95%91%E4%BA%BA%E6%88%96%E5%85%88%E8%87%AA%E6%95%91-%E6%B3%95%E5%BE%8B%E9%81%93%E5%BE%B7%E5%85%B7%E7%88%AD%E8%AD%B0-224632742.html|accessdate=5 October 2012|date=3 October 2012}}</ref> At first, reports stated that the captain continued on to the pier out of passenger request and out of fear that ''Sea Smooth'' herself might sink, but later reports also claimed that some passengers urged the captain to stop.<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u6e21\u8f2a\u5ba2\u547c\u505c\u8239 \u8239\u9577\u4e0d\u7406 \u6536\u96c6\u6551\u751f\u8863 \u64ec\u62cb\u6d77\u6551\u4eba(Chinese)|url=http://hk.news.yahoo.com/%E6%B8%A1%E8%BC%AA%E5%AE%A2%E5%91%BC%E5%81%9C%E8%88%B9-%E8%88%B9%E9%95%B7%E4%B8%8D%E7%90%86-%E6%94%B6%E9%9B%86%E6%95%91%E7%94%9F%E8%A1%A3-%E6%93%AC%E6%8B%8B%E6%B5%B7%E6%95%91%E4%BA%BA-212119092.html|accessdate=5 October 2012|date=3 October 2012}}</ref> In the few days following the accident, the captain had remained emotionally unstable even after being discharged from the hospital.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Captain of Sea Smooth discharged, emotionally unstable (Chinese)|url=http://hk.news.yahoo.com/%E6%B5%B7%E6%B3%B0%E8%88%B9%E9%95%B7%E5%87%BA%E9%99%A2-%E9%8C%84%E5%8F%A3%E4%BE%9B%E6%83%85%E7%B7%92%E6%9C%AA%E7%A9%A9-223000610.html|accessdate=5 October 2012|date=3 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter he was informed of the accident, Chief Executive Leung Chun-ying immediately set out to the scene to oversee the rescue efforts.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://orientaldaily.on.cc/cnt/news/20121002/00176_010.html|title=Leung overseeing rescue on scene|accessdate=5 October 2012|date=2 October 2012|work=Oriental Daily}}</ref> Some media{{which|date=October 2012}} suggested it was a \"political show\", and said that his presence might have actually slowed down the rescue.\n\nLeung was also criticised{{by whom|date=October 2012}} for his decision to ask for help from Mainland China through the [[Liaison Office of the Central People's Government in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region|Liaison Office of the Central People's Government]], despite the abundance of manpower and resources already in Hong Kong. Many{{who|date=October 2012}} saw this as increased influence and reliance on the [[Government of the People's Republic of China|Central government]], a change from the previous [[Donald Tsang|Tsang]] administration.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Looking at Hong Kong-Chinese relationship from disaster|url=http://www.vjmedia.com.hk/articles/2012/10/02/20887|accessdate=5 October 2012|date=2 October 2012}}</ref> Also, despite Leung's clarification that no ship from Mainland China had been deployed in the rescue, on 3 October Mainland China's [[China News Service]] reported that \"95 people had been rescued by the professional Chinese rescue fleet\".<ref>{{Cite news|title=Ferry crash response revives distrust between Hong Kong and mainland China|url=http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/regions/asia-pacific/china/121003/ferry-crash-response-revives-distrust-between-hong-k|accessdate=5 October 2012|author=Carlson, Benjamin |work=Global Post |date=3 October 2012}}</ref> The news agency later deleted the number rescued, but the report had not been fully withdrawn and the claim remained that Chinese ships had helped in the rescue.<ref>{{Cite news|title=95 rescued in a dubious claim by Chinese News Service|url=http://hk.apple.nextmedia.com/news/art/20121003/18031122|accessdate=5 October 2012|date=3 October 2012 |work=Apple Daily}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.coi-lamma.gov.hk/eng/index.html Commission of Inquiry into the Collision of Vessels near Lamma Island on 1 October 2012]\n*[[Marine Department (Hong Kong)|Marine Department]]\n**\"[http://www.mardep.gov.hk/en/news/pdf/tf_pn20160831.pdf Report of a Public Inquiry, Convened Pursuant to s 17, Merchant Shipping (Local Vessels) Ordinance Cap 548.]\" \n**\"[http://www.mardep.gov.hk/en/aboutus/pdf/lvac_jsc_p1201.pdf Paper No. 1/2012 LOCAL VESSELS ADVISORY COMMITTEE  Meeting of Joint Sub-committee on Class I and Class IV Vessels Traffic control and safety measures for fireworks displays and other major events ].\"\n\n{{2012 shipwrecks}}\n\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 2012]]\n[[Category:2012 in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Ships sunk in collisions]]\n[[Category:Ferries]]\n[[Category:Shipwrecks of Hong Kong]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2012_Lamma_Island_ferry_collision"}
{"title_page": "Shaftesbury", "text_new": "{{about|the town in Dorset, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n| official_name= Shaftesbury\n| static_image_name= High Street, Shaftesbury - geograph.org.uk - 1440129.jpg\n| static_image_caption= High Street\n| map_type= Dorset\n| coordinates= {{coord|51.0059|-2.1969|display=inline,title}}\n| population= 7,314\n| population_ref= ([[2011 United Kingdom census|2011]])<ref name=ons>{{cite web |title=Area: Shaftesbury (Parish). Key Figures for 2011 Census: Key Statistics |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11128341&c=Shaftesbury&d=16&e=62&g=6418052&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&o=362&m=0&r=1&s=1433061124578&enc=1 |work=Neighbourhood Statistics |publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref>\n| os_grid_reference= ST861228\n| london_distance=\n| civil_parish= Shaftesbury\n| unitary_england= [[Dorset (unitary authority)|Dorset]]\n| lieutenancy_england= [[Dorset]]\n| region= South West England\n| country= England\n| post_town= SHAFTESBURY\n| postcode_area= SP\n| postcode_district= SP7\n| dial_code= 01747\n| constituency_westminster= [[North Dorset (constituency)|North Dorset]]\n}}\n[[File:Milestone, Blandford Forum - geograph.org.uk - 1714569.jpg|thumb|upright|Old milestone in [[Blandford Forum]] showing use of the name Shaston for Shaftesbury]]\n\n'''Shaftesbury''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0283|\u0251\u02d0|f|t|s|b|\u0259r|i|,_|\u02c8|\u0283|\u00e6|f|t|s|-}}) is a town and [[civil parish]] in [[Dorset]], England. It is situated on the [[A30 road]], {{convert|20|miles|km|0}} west of [[Salisbury, Wiltshire|Salisbury]], near to the border with [[Wiltshire]]. It is the only significant hilltop settlement in Dorset, being built about {{convert|215|m|ft}} [[Above mean sea level|above sea level]] on a [[greensand]] hill on the edge of [[Cranborne Chase]]. Shaftesbury also refers to a former carehome, located in Exeter, prominent during the 20th and early 21st centuries.  \n\nThe town looks over the [[Blackmore Vale]], part of the [[River Stour, Dorset|River Stour]] basin. From different viewpoints, it is possible to see at least as far as [[Glastonbury Tor]] to the northwest.\n\nShaftesbury is the site of the former [[Shaftesbury Abbey]], which was founded in 888 by [[Alfred the Great|King Alfred]] and became one of the richest religious establishments in the country, before being destroyed in the [[Dissolution of the Monasteries|Dissolution]] in 1539. Adjacent to the abbey site is [[Gold Hill, Shaftesbury|Gold Hill]], a steep [[Cobblestone|cobbled]] street used in the 1970s as the setting for [[Ridley Scott]]{{'}}s television advertisement for [[Hovis]] bread.\n\nIn the [[2011 United Kingdom census|2011 Census]] the town's civil parish had a population of 7,314. \nShaftesbury house is currently home to a population of 9.  \n\n==Toponymy==\nShaftesbury has acquired a number of names throughout its history. Writing in 1906, [[Sir Frederick Treves, 1st Baronet|Sir Frederick Treves]] referred to four of these names from Celtic, Latin and English traditions in his book ''Highways & Byways in Dorset'':\n{{quote|text=The city has had many names. It was, in the beginning, Caer Palladour. By the time of the Domesday Book it was Sceptesberie. It then, with all the affectation of a lady in an eighteenth-century lyric, called itself Sophonia. Lastly it became Shaston, and so the people call it to this day, while all the milestones around concern themselves only with recording the distances to \"Shaston\".|sign=Sir Frederick Treves|source=Highways & Byways in Dorset (1906)}}\n\nThe original [[Common Brittonic|Celtic]] name is first recorded in [[Medieval Welsh literature]] as ''Caer Vynnydd y Paladr'' (The Mountain Fort/City of the Spears)<ref>[[Brut y Brenhinedd]] (mid 13th century document largely regarded as an accurate account of the early history of the Britons)</ref> and [[Thomas Gale]] records the name as ''Caer Palladour'' in his work of 1709.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gale |first1=Thomas |title=Antonini iter Britanniarum commentariis illustratum |date=1709 |location=London |page=132 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cm5bAAAAQAAJ&pg=PT1&lpg=PT1&dq=Caer+Palladour&source=bl&ots=tfI8Uof9hJ&sig=ACfU3U1sJLg9Iw2hbSX8MY6EIj-_kPAeyw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjWkvLOko7oAhWSX8AKHXp8AxgQ6AEwCXoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false |language=Latin}}</ref> Though \"Palladour\" was described by one 19th-century directory as \"mere invention\", it has continued to be used as a poetic and alternative name for the town.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SZYIAAAAQAAJ&pg=RA1-PA134&lpg=RA1-PA134&dq=sophonia+shaftesbury&source=bl&ots=oZXmxEnpRC&sig=3bVaZjF_K-1I33h0bTLFychYy1w&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-v2LUsXKL4TBhAf4xoDoDQ&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=sophonia%20shaftesbury&f=false|title=Topographical and Statistical Description of the County of Dorset|last=Cooke|first=George Alexander|year=|publisher=|page=134|accessdate=20 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe English name was recorded in the [[Domesday Book]] as Sceptesberie,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Domesday Book Online. Dorset S-Z|publisher=domesdaybook.co.uk|year=1999\u20132013|accessdate=19 November 2013|url=http://www.domesdaybook.co.uk/dorset3.html}}</ref> and the use of \"Shaston\" ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0283|\u00e6|s|t|\u0259n}}) was recorded in 1831 in Samuel Lewis's ''A Topographical Dictionary of England''<ref name=\"Lewis1831\">{{cite book|last=Lewis|first=Samuel |title=A Topographical Dictionary of England|url=https://archive.org/details/atopographicald00lewigoog|accessdate=17 December 2012|year=1831|publisher=S. Lewis|page=[https://archive.org/details/atopographicald00lewigoog/page/n67 61]}}</ref> and in 1840 in ''The parliamentary gazetteer of England and Wales''.<ref name=\"gazetteer1840\">{{cite book|author=England|title=The parliamentary gazetteer of England and Wales|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uNgHAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA94|accessdate=17 December 2012|year=1840|page=94}}</ref>\n\n[[Thomas Hardy]] used both \"Shaston\" and \"Palladour\" to refer to the town in the fictional [[Thomas Hardy's Wessex|Wessex]] of his novels such as ''[[Jude the Obscure]]''<ref>{{cite book|last=Ross|first=Alexander|title=The Imprint of the Picturesque on Nineteenth-century British Fiction|url=https://archive.org/details/imprintofpicture0000ross|url-access=registration|quote=palladour tess.|accessdate=19 November 2013|publisher=Wilfrid Laurier Univ. Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/imprintofpicture0000ross/page/136 136]|year=1986}}</ref>\n\nShaftesbury house also has a variety of terms linked to it, most prominently the 'shaftening', a generic term applied to activities that take place within the house. \n==History==\nThere is no substantive evidence that Shaftesbury was the \"Caer Palladur\" (or \"Caer Palladwr\") of Celtic and Roman times, and instead the town's recorded history dates from [[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo-Saxon times]].<ref>{{cite book|title=North Dorset District Official Guide|publisher=Home Publishing Company Ltd|pages=23\u201324|author=North Dorset District Council|year=c. 1983}}</ref> By the early 8th century there was an important minster church here,<ref name=\"Bettey, pp 62-63\">Bettey, pp 62-63</ref> and in 880 [[Alfred the Great]] founded a [[burgh]] (fortified settlement) here as a defence in the struggle with the [[Danes (Germanic tribe)|Danish]] invaders.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}} The burgh is recorded in the early-10th-century [[Burghal Hidage]] as one of only three that existed in the county (the others being at [[Wareham, Dorset|Wareham]] and 'Bredy' - which is probably [[Bridport]]).<ref name=\"Bettey, pp 62-63\"/>\n[[File:Ruins of Shaftesbury Abbey (geograph 3605823).jpg|thumb|left|The ruins of [[Shaftesbury Abbey]]]]\n\nIn 888 Alfred founded [[Shaftesbury Abbey]], a [[Benedictine]] [[nunnery]] by the town's east gate, and appointed his daughter Ethelgifu as the first [[abbess]].<ref>Bettey, p30</ref> [[\u00c6thelstan]] founded two royal mints,<ref name=hyams>{{cite book |title=Dorset |first=John |last=Hyams |publisher=B. T. Batsford Ltd |year=1970 |page=197 |isbn=0-7134-0066-8}}</ref> which struck pennies bearing the town's name, and the abbey became the wealthiest Benedictine nunnery in England. On 20 February 981 the relics of St [[Edward the Martyr]], the teenage King of England, were transferred from Wareham and received at the abbey with great ceremony, thereafter turning Shaftesbury into a major site of pilgrimage for miracles of healing.\n\n[[Cnut the Great|King Canute]] died here in 1035, though he was buried at [[Winchester]].<ref name=hyams/> [[Edward the Confessor]] licensed a third mint for the town.<ref name=hyams/> By the time of the [[Norman conquest of England|Norman conquest]] in 1066 Shaftesbury had 257 houses, though many were destroyed in the ensuing years of conflict, and by the time the [[Domesday Book]] was compiled twenty years later, there were only 177 houses remaining, though this still meant that Shaftesbury was the largest town in Dorset at that time.<ref>Bettey, p63</ref> Around this time the town's ownership was equally shared between king and abbey.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}} In the [[The Anarchy|first English civil war]] (1135-1154) between [[Empress Matilda]] and [[Stephen, King of England|King Stephen]], an [[adulterine castle]] or fortified house was built on a small [[promontory]] at the western edge of the hill on which the old town was built. The site on Castle Hill, also known locally as Boltbury, is now under grass and is a [[scheduled monument]].<ref name=gatehouse>{{cite web |url=http://www.gatehouse-gazetteer.info/English%20sites/956.html |title=Shaftesbury Castle Hill |publisher=gatehouse-gazetteer |date=29 May 2015 |accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1240 Cardinal Otto ([[Oddone di Monferrato]]), legate to the [[Apostolic See]] of [[Pope Gregory IX]] visited the abbey and confirmed a charter of 1191, the first entered in the Glastonbury chartulary. During the [[Middle Ages]] the abbey was the central focus of the town; the abbey's great wealth was acknowledged in a popular saying at the time, which stated that \"If the abbot of Glastonbury could marry the abbess of Shaftesbury their heir would hold more land than the king of England\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/dorset/vol2/pp73-79 |title='House of Benedictine nuns: The abbey of Shaftesbury', in A History of the County of Dorset: Volume 2, ed. William Page (London, 1908), pp. 73-79 |publisher=University of London |accessdate=13 May 2015 |work=British History Online}}</ref> In 1260 a charter to hold a market was granted. By 1340 the mayor had become a recognised figure, sworn in by the steward of the abbess. In 1392 [[Richard II of England|Richard II]] confirmed a grant of two markets on different days. Edwardstow, Shaftesbury's oldest surviving building, was built on Bimport at some time between 1400 and 1539. Also in this period a medieval farm owned by the Abbess of Shaftesbury was established, on a site now occupied by the Tesco supermarket car park.\n[[File:Edwardstowe, Shaftesbury - geograph.org.uk - 224159.jpg|thumb|Edwardstow]]\n\nIn 1539, the last Abbess of Shaftesbury, Elizabeth Zouche, signed a deed of surrender, the (by then extremely wealthy) abbey was demolished, and its lands sold, leading to a temporary decline in the town. [[Thomas Arundell of Wardour Castle|Sir Thomas Arundell]] purchased the abbey and much of the town in 1540, but when he was later exiled for treason his lands were forfeit, and the lands passed to Pembroke then [[Anthony Ashley-Cooper, 7th Earl of Shaftesbury]], and finally to the Grosvenors.\n\nShaftesbury was a parliamentary constituency returning two members from 1296 to the [[Reform Act 1832|Reform Act of 1832]], when it was reduced to one, and in 1884 the separate constituency was abolished.\n\nIn ''Survey of Dorsetshire'', written in about 1630 by Thomas Gerard of the Dorset village of [[Trent, Dorset|Trent]], Shaftesbury is described as a \"faire Thorough Faire, much frequented by Travellers to and from London\".<ref>Bettey, p129</ref>\n\nThe town was broadly Parliamentarian in the [[English Civil War|Civil War]], but was in Royalist hands. [[Wardour Castle]] fell to Parliamentary forces in 1643; Parliamentary forces surrounded the town in August 1645, when it was a centre of local [[clubmen]] activity. The clubmen were arrested and sent to trial in [[Sherborne]]. Shaftesbury took no part in the [[Monmouth Rebellion]] of 1685.\n\nIn the 17th century the cloth industry formed part of Shaftesbury's economy, though much of the actual production took place as a [[cottage industry]] in the surrounding area. In the 18th century the town produced a coarse white woollen cloth called 'swanskin', that was used by fishermen of [[Newfoundland]] and for uniforms.<ref>Bettey, pp 75-76</ref> [[Dorset button|Buttonmaking]] also became important around this time, though with the later advent of [[Industrial Revolution|industrialisation]] this subsequently declined, resulting in unemployment, starvation and emigration, with 350 families leaving for [[Canada]].<ref name=loaf>{{cite web|url=http://www.dorsetlife.co.uk/2009/08/more-to-it-than-a-brown-loaf/|title=More to it than a brown loaf|date=August 2009|author=Tony Burton-Page|publisher=Dorset Life|accessdate=20 November 2013}}</ref> [[Malting]] and [[brewing]] were also significant in the 17th and 18th centuries, and like other Dorset towns such as [[Dorchester, Dorset|Dorchester]] and [[Blandford Forum]], Shaftesbury became known for its beer.<ref name=Bettey81>Bettey, p81</ref>\n\nIn the 18th century the [[Toll road|turnpike road]]s which met at Shaftesbury ensured that the town had a good coaching trade.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}} The railways however bypassed the town, which had consequences for Shaftesbury's economy; during the 19th century the town's brewing industry was reduced to serving only local markets, as towns elsewhere in the country could transport their produce more cheaply.<ref name=Bettey81/> During the 19th century the population of the town grew little.<ref>Bettey, pp 72-73</ref>\n\n[[File:Shaftesbury Town Hall - geograph.org.uk - 1436981.jpg|thumb|left|St Peter's Church and the town hall]]\nThe town hall was built in 1827 by Earl Grosvenor after the guildhall was pulled down to widen High Street. It has been designated by [[English Heritage]] as a grade II listed building.<ref>{{cite web | title=The Town Hall | work=historicengland.org.uk | url=https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1108741 | accessdate=29 December 2007}}</ref> The town hall is next to the 15th-century St Peter's Church.<ref>{{cite web | title=Church of St Peter | work=historicengland.org.uk | url=https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1292132 | accessdate=29 December 2007}}</ref> The [[Westminster Memorial Hospital]] was constructed on Bimport in the mid-19th century with a legacy from the wife of the [[Richard Grosvenor, 2nd Marquess of Westminster|Duke of Westminster]].<ref>''The Cottage Hospitals 1859-1990''. Dr Meyrick Emrys-Roberts, 1991. Tern Publications, Motcombe, Dorset. {{ISBN|0951713604}}</ref>\n\nIn 1918 Lord Stalbridge sold a large portion of the town, which was purchased by a syndicate and auctioned piece by piece over three days.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dorsetlife.co.uk/2008/03/the-fall-of-the-house-of-stalbridge/ |title=The fall of the House of Stalbridge |publisher=Dorset Life Magazine |date=March 2008 |author=Alan J Miller |accessdate=19 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nMost of Shaftesbury's buildings date from no earlier than the 18th century, as the [[Saxons|Saxon]] and most of the medieval buildings have not survived.\n\nDuring the 1950s and onwards a large amount of low-cost housing has been established around the outskirts of Shaftesbury{{Citation needed|date=December 2012}}.\nAt present, the house continues to be occupied by 9 'shafters'. \n\n==Governance==\nIn the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|United Kingdom national parliament]], Shaftesbury is in the [[North Dorset (UK Parliament constituency)|North Dorset parliamentary constituency]] which is currently [[Member of Parliament|represented]] by [[Simon Hoare]] of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative party]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000839 |title=Dorset North Parliamentary constituency |work=Election 2015 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref> At the top tier of [[local government]] Shaftesbury is governed by [[Dorset County Council]], the main responsibilities of which include schools and other education, highways, planning, waste, public transport, social care, countryside and heritage, public health, libraries, museums and the arts, archives, trading standards and planning for emergencies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dorsetforyou.com/article/387750/Dorset-County-Council---budget-books |title=The Budget Book 2014 - 2015 (pdf) |publisher=Dorset County Council |work=dorsetforyou.com |accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref> At the middle tier of local government Shaftesbury is governed by North Dorset District Council. Since 2006 North Dorset District Council has reduced its direct service provision via a system of decentralised community partnerships with local organisations such as town councils.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.reform.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/North_Dorset_District_Council.pdf |title=North Dorset District Council |work=reform.uk |accessdate=16 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925133402/http://www.reform.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/North_Dorset_District_Council.pdf |archive-date=25 September 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> North Dorset District Council is also in a 'tri-council' partnership with two other district-level councils in Dorset, West Dorset District Council and Weymouth and Portland Borough Council; the aim of the partnership is to reduce costs of management and buildings.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-dorset-31542441 |title=North Dorset approves 'tri-council' partnership |publisher=BBC |date=19 February 2015 |accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref> At the bottom tier of local government Shaftesbury is governed by Shaftesbury Town Council,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://towncouncil.shaftesburydorset.com/ |title=Welcome to Shaftesbury Town Council |publisher=Shaftesbury Town Council |work=shaftesburydorset.com |accessdate=6 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150405023327/http://towncouncil.shaftesburydorset.com/ |archive-date=5 April 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> which has responsibilities that include open spaces and recreational facilities, allotments, litter, street markets, public conveniences, grants to voluntary organisations, cemetery provision, bus shelters, crime prevention initiatives, civic events and the town hall, planning (as a consultee) and the war memorial.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shaftesburytowncouncil.co.uk/about/what-we-do |title=What We Do |publisher=Shaftesbury Town Council |accessdate=16 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150802205252/http://www.shaftesburytowncouncil.co.uk/about/what-we-do |archivedate=2 August 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFor electoral purposes Shaftesbury is divided into two [[Wards and electoral divisions of the United Kingdom|electoral wards]]: Shaftesbury West and Shaftesbury East. In national parliamentary elections these are joined with 25 other wards that together elect the Member of Parliament for the North Dorset constituency.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.electoralcalculus.co.uk/cgi-bin/seatdetails.pl?seat=Dorset%20North |title=Dorset North: Seat, Ward and Prediction Details |publisher=electoralcalculus.co.uk |accessdate=16 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925122148/http://www.electoralcalculus.co.uk/cgi-bin/seatdetails.pl?seat=Dorset%20North |archivedate=25 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In county council elections the two wards together form Shaftesbury electoral division, one of 42 divisions that each elect councillors to Dorset County Council.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dorsetforyou.com/390881 |title=Electoral division profiles 2013 |publisher=Dorset County Council |work=dorsetforyou.com |date= |accessdate=6 May 2015}}</ref> The county council has 45 councillors (three divisions elect two councillors each)<ref name=committee>{{cite web |url=http://www1.dorsetforyou.com/Council/COMMIS2013.nsf/MEM?OpenView&Count=1000 |title=Committee Information |publisher=Dorset County Council |work=dorsetforyou.com |accessdate=16 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925095104/http://www1.dorsetforyou.com/Council/COMMIS2013.nsf/MEM?OpenView&Count=1000 |archivedate=25 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and the Conservative Party has overall control,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dorsetforyou.com/councillors/county |title=Dorset county councillors |publisher=Dorset County Council |work=dorsetforyou.com |date=17 January 2015 |accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref> though the councillor representing Shaftesbury is a [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]].<ref name=committee/> In district council elections the two wards, together with seventeen other wards within the [[North Dorset|North Dorset District]], elect councillors to North Dorset District Council; the two Shaftesbury wards each elect two councillors<ref name=legislation>{{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukdsi/2014/9780111115473?view=plain |title=The North Dorset (Electoral Changes) Order 2014 |publisher= |work=legislation.gov.uk |accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref> out of a total of 33. The Conservative Party has overall control of the district council, though of the four councillors that represent Shaftesbury, one is a Liberal Democrat and one is an [[Independent politician|independent]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dorsetforyou.com/councillors/north |title=North Dorset district councillors |publisher=Dorset County Council |work=dorsetforyou.com |date=5 September 2014 |accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref> In town council elections Shaftesbury's two wards each elect six councillors to Shaftesbury Town Council.<ref name=legislation/> The mayor of Shaftesbury for 2016-17 is Dr Richard Tippins.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shaftesburytowncouncil.co.uk/who-we-are |title=Who We Are |publisher=Shaftesbury Town Council |accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Viewpoint, Park Walk,Shaftesbury - geograph.org.uk - 1436844.jpg|thumb|Looking south from the town towards [[Melbury Hill]], from Park Walk]]\n\n==Geography==\nThe old centre of Shaftesbury is sited on a westward-pointing [[promontory]] of high ground in northeast Dorset, on the [[escarpment|scarp edge]] of a range of hills that extend south and east into [[Cranborne Chase]] and neighbouring [[Wiltshire]].<ref name=Survey2013>Ordnance Survey (2013), 1:25,000 Explorer Map, Sheet 118 (Shaftesbury and Cranborne Chase), {{ISBN|978-0-319-24123-3}}</ref><ref>John Bartholomew & Son Ltd (1980), 1:100,000 National Map Series, Sheet 4 (Dorset), {{ISBN|0-7028-0327-8}}</ref> The town's built-up area also extends down the promontory slopes to lower ground at St James, Alcester and Enmore Green, and eastwards across the [[Drainage divide|watershed]] towards the hill's dip slope.<ref name=Survey2013/> Shaftesbury's altitude is between about {{convert|165|m|ft}} at the lowest streets below the promontory, to about {{convert|235|m|ft}} at Wincombe Business Park on the hilltop in the north, with the promontory and town centre being at about {{convert|215|m|ft}}.<ref name=Survey2013/> Below the town to the west is the [[Blackmore Vale]], which undulates between about {{convert|60|m|ft}} and {{convert|110|m|ft}}.<ref>Ornance Survey (2005), 1:50,000 Landranger Map, Sheet 183 (Yeovil & Frome), {{ISBN|978-0-319-22861-6}}</ref> About {{convert|2|miles|km|0}} to the west of the town and within the Blackmore Vale is the conical mound of [[Duncliffe Hill]], visible for miles and home to Duncliffe Wood and a nature reserve. The countryside east of the town is part of the [[Cranborne Chase and West Wiltshire Downs]] [[Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ccwwdaonb.org.uk/docs/General_MapSW.pdf |title=Cranborne Chase & West Wiltshire Downs Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty |publisher=ccwwdaonb.org.uk |accessdate=27 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130808041911/http://ccwwdaonb.org.uk/docs/General_MapSW.pdf |archivedate=8 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nGeologically, Shaftesbury's hill mostly comprises [[Greensand|Upper Greensand]], which is overlain by Lower [[Chalk]] in the east. These date from the [[Cretaceous]], with the greensand having been formed in the [[Albian]] and early [[Cenomanian]], and the chalk also in the Cenomanian. The greensand is composed of three [[Bed (geology)|beds]]: the oldest and lowest is a layer of Cann Sand, which is found in the lower parts of the town, such as St James and Alcester, that are below the promontory; above this is a layer of Shaftesbury Sandstone, which generally forms the steepest slopes around the promontory, and on top of this is a layer of Boyne Hollow Chert, which is found on top of the hill and on which most of the town is built. Below the Cann Sand, on the lower slopes of the hill to the north, west and south of the town, are extensive landslip deposits.<ref>British Geological Survey (1994), 1:50,000 Series England and Wales Sheet 313, Shaftesbury Solid and Drift Geology, {{ISBN|0-7518-2823-8}}</ref>\n[[File:High Street ,Shaftesbury, Dorset - geograph.org.uk - 411160.jpg|thumb|left|Businesses on High Street]]\n\n==Economy==\nIn 2012 there were 3,400 people employed in Shaftesbury, 65% of whom were working full-time and 35% part-time.<ref name=profile>{{cite web|url=https://www.dorsetforyou.com/article/343604/Shaftesbury-town-profile |title=Shaftesbury town profile |publisher=Dorset County Council / archive.org |work=dorsetforyou.com |date=3 November 2014 |accessdate=16 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710020114/https://www.dorsetforyou.com/article/343604/Shaftesbury-town-profile |archivedate=10 July 2015 }}</ref> Excluding agriculture, the most important employment sectors were public administration, education and health (31% of non-agricultural employment), production and construction (29%), and distribution, accommodation and food (26%).<ref name=profile/> Significant employers include [[Dorset County Council]], [[Pork Farms]], [[Guys Marsh (HM Prison)|Guys Marsh Prison]], [[Royal Mail]], [[Somerfield]], [[Tesco]], [[Port Regis School]], Wessex Electricals, Stalbridge Linen Services, Blackmore Press and Dorset Chilled Foods.<ref name=profile/> There are two industrial estates in the town: Longmead Industrial Estate, covering {{convert|7.7|ha|acre}}, and Wincombe Business Park, covering {{convert|6.5|ha|acre}}.<ref name=profile/>\n\nIn 2005 there were 75 shops in the town, with a total floorspace of {{convert|78000|sqft|sqm}}. The retail catchment area for major food shopping extends about {{convert|4.5|mi|km}} in all directions. National retail [[chain store|chains]] with a presence in the town include [[the Body Shop]], [[Boots UK|Boots]], Somerfield, [[Superdrug]], Tesco and [[WHSmith]].<ref name=profile/>\n\nA site has been identified for a projected parkway station on the [[West of England]] main railway line. It would be situated to the north of the town, beneath the A350 road, and a bus service would connect it with the town.{{Citation needed|date=April 2013}} Currently the nearest railway station is located in neighbouring [[Gillingham, Dorset|Gillingham]].\n\n==Demography==\nIn the [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 census]] Shaftesbury's civil parish had 3,493 dwellings,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=11128341&c=Shaftesbury&d=16&e=62&g=6418052&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&o=362&m=0&r=1&s=1433061469234&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2481 |title=Area: Shaftesbury (Parish). Dwellings, Household Spaces and Accommodation Type, 2011 (KS401EW)|publisher=Office for National Statistics |work=Neighbourhood Statistics |accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> 3,235 households and a population of 7,314.<ref name=ons/> The average age of inhabitants was 43, compared to 39.3 for England as a whole. 22.1% of inhabitants were age 65 or older, compared to 16.4% for England as a whole.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=11128341&c=Shaftesbury&d=16&e=62&g=6418052&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1431763097508&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2474 |title=Area: Shaftesbury (Parish). Age Structure, 2011 (KS102EW) |publisher=Office for National Statistics |work=Neighbourhood Statistics |accessdate=16 May 2015}}</ref> 92% of Shaftesbury's residents were born in the United Kingdom, compared to 86.2% for England as a whole.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=11128341&c=Shaftesbury&d=16&e=62&g=6418052&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1433060431375&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2478 |title=Area: Shaftesbury (Parish). Country of Birth, 2011 (KS204EW) |publisher=Office for National Statistics |work=Neighbourhood Statistics |accessdate=31 May 2015}}</ref> Previous census figures for the total population of the civil parish are shown in the table below:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:800px;\"\n! colspan= \"15\" style=\"background:; color:\" | <span style=\"margin-left: 80px; color: \">Census Population of Shaftesbury Parish 1921\u20142001 <small>(except 1941)</small></span>\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background:; color: height:15px;\"| Census\n! style=\"background:;\"| 1921\n! style=\"background:;\"| 1931\n! style=\"background:;\"| 1951\n! style=\"background:;\"| 1961\n! style=\"background:;\"| 1971\n! style=\"background:;\"| 1981\n! style=\"background:;\"| 1991\n! style=\"background:;\"| 2001\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background:; color: height:15px;\"|Population\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2;\"| *1,812\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2;\"| *2,819\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2;\"| *3,303\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2;\"| 3,372\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2;\"| 3,980\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2;\"| 3,940\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2;\"| 6,180\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2;\"| 6,680\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| colspan=\"15\" style=\"background:#F2F2F2; color: text-align:center;\"| <small>Asterisks (*) indicate a boundary change<br>Source:Dorset County Council<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dorsetforyou.com/article/345043/Parishes-M-Z-1921-2001-Census-Years |title=Parishes (M-Z), 1921-2001 Census Years |publisher=Dorset County Council |work=dorsetforyou.com |accessdate=23 May 2015 |date=27 May 2014}}</ref>\n</small>\n|}\n\n==Culture, art and media==\n[[File:Snowdrop Festival, Shaftesbury (12673314263).jpg|thumb|right|Shaftesbury Snowdrops]]\nShaftesbury Arts Centre was established in 1957 and stages a variety of exhibitions, performances, workshops and training courses. It is based in the old covered market in the town centre and is a charitable company that is run wholly by its volunteer members.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shaftesburyartscentre.org.uk/about-us |title=About Us |publisher=Shaftesbury Arts Centre |accessdate=30 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511002716/http://www.shaftesburyartscentre.org.uk/about-us |archivedate=11 May 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nShaftesbury has two museums: Gold Hill Museum at the top of Gold Hill, and Shaftesbury Abbey Museum in the abbey grounds.<ref name=loaf/><ref name=abbeymuseum>{{cite web |url=http://shaftesburyabbey.org.uk/ |title=Shaftesbury Abbey Museum & Gardens |publisher=Shaftesbury Abbey Museum & Gardens |accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref> Gold Hill Museum was founded in 1946 and displays many artefacts that relate to the history of Shaftesbury and the surrounding area, including Dorset's oldest fire engine, dating from 1744.<ref name=loaf/> Shaftesbury Abbey Museum tells the story of the abbey and also has a herb garden and medieval orchard.<ref name=abbeymuseum/>\n\nShaftesbury Snowdrops is a Diamond Jubilee Community Legacy with the aim of creating a series of free and accessible [[Galanthus nivalis|snowdrop]] walks by planting snowdrops within the publicly open spaces and along the pathways throughout the town. The project was started in the winter of 2012 with the planting of 60,000 bulbs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hundreds of Shaftesbury snowdrops planted after Diamond Jubilee|url=http://www.blackmorevale.co.uk/Hundreds-Shaftesbury-snowdrops-planted-Diamond/story-17587450-detail/story.html|website=www.blackmorevale.co.uk|publisher=Blackmore Vale Magazine|accessdate=22 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122152504/http://www.blackmorevale.co.uk/Hundreds-Shaftesbury-snowdrops-planted-Diamond/story-17587450-detail/story.html|archivedate=22 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Since 2013 there has been an annual Snowdrop Festival to encourage tourists to see the snowdrops in flower.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shaftesbury celebrates the snowdrop|url=http://www.blackmorevale.co.uk/Shaftesbury-celebrates-snowdrop/story-18090175-detail/story.html|website=www.blackmorevale.co.uk|publisher=Blackmore Vale Magazine|accessdate=22 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122150948/http://www.blackmorevale.co.uk/Shaftesbury-celebrates-snowdrop/story-18090175-detail/story.html|archivedate=22 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Highlights of the festival include the Snowdrop Art Exhibition<ref>{{cite web|title=Shaftesbury Snowdrop Festival Art Exhibition 2013|url=http://www.blackmorevale.co.uk/pictures/PHOTOS-Shaftesbury-Snowdrop-Festival-Art/pictures-18182409-detail/pictures.html|website=www.blackmorevale.co.uk|publisher=Blackmore Vale Magazine|accessdate=22 January 2015}}</ref> and the Snowdrop Lantern Parade.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shaftesbury Snowdrop Festival - starts 15th Feb|url=http://www.blackmorevale.co.uk/pictures/PHOTOS-Shaftesbury-Snowdrop-Festival-starts-15th/pictures-20519657-detail/pictures.html|website=www.blackmorevale.co.uk|publisher=Blackmore Vale Magazine|accessdate=22 January 2015}}</ref> In 2014 Shaftesbury Snowdrops started a heritage collection of rare and unusual snowdrops.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shaftesbury Snowdrops Heritage Collection launched|url=http://www.blackmorevale.co.uk/PHOTOS-Shaftesbury-Snowdrops-Heritage-Collection/story-20643190-detail/story.html|website=www.blackmorevale.co.uk|publisher=Blackmore Vale Magazine|accessdate=22 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122125355/http://www.blackmorevale.co.uk/PHOTOS-Shaftesbury-Snowdrops-Heritage-Collection/story-20643190-detail/story.html|archivedate=22 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  These are held in trust for the people of Shaftesbury and displayed in Shaftesbury Abbey during the annual Snowdrop Festival. The collection is being built through sponsorship and donations.\n\nGold Hill Fair usually occurs in the first weekend of July and has food stalls, arts stalls and local music that can be found in the abbey ruins.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://shaftesburyrotaryclub.org/upcoming-events/gold-hill-fair/|title=Gold Hill Fair - Shaftesbury Rotary Club|work=Shaftesbury Rotary Club|access-date=2017-05-12|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n[[File:Gold Hill, Shaftsbury, Dorset, England.JPG|thumb|Steep, [[cobblestones|cobbled]] Gold Hill, with a [[buttress]]ed wall to the right, a [[scheduled monument]] on the edge of Shaftesbury Abbey [[religious precinct|precinct]]<ref>[https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1004559 Abbey precinct wall on Gold Hill], [[Historic England]], 17 September 2019. Retrieved 17 September 2019</ref>]]\n\n===Representations===\n[[Thomas Hardy]] used the names ''Shaston'' or ''Palladour'' to describe Shaftesbury in the fictional [[Thomas Hardy's Wessex|Wessex]] of his novels. In ''[[Jude the Obscure]]'' he described the loss of the town's former architectural glories, principally the abbey:\n\n''\"Vague imaginings of its castle, its three mints, its magnificent apsidal abbey, the chief glory of south Wessex, its twelve churches, its shrines, chantries, hospitals, its gabled freestone mansions\u2014all now ruthlessly swept away\u2014throw the visitor, even against his will, into a pensive melancholy, which the stimulating atmosphere and limitless landscape around him can scarcely dispel.\"''<ref>In: Hardy, Thomas (1895). ''[[Jude the Obscure]]'', [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=oTIgSfMC3akC&lpg=PA356&dq=%22Shaston%2C%20the%20ancient%22&pg=PA356#v=onepage&q=%22Shaston,%20the%20ancient%22&f=false part fourth, chapter I]. Retrieved 17 December 2011.</ref>\n\nIn the 1970s [[Ridley Scott]] used [[Gold Hill, Shaftesbury|Gold Hill]], a steep cobbled street in the town, as the setting for a television advertisement for [[Hovis]] bread, in which a bread delivery boy is seen pushing his bicycle up the street before freewheeling back down. The advertisement made the street nationally famous.<ref name=loaf/>\n\n==Transport==\n{{expand section|date=June 2018}}\nShaftesbury is served by the [[A30 road (Great Britain)|A30]] between London and Exeter, and the [[A350 road (Great Britain)|A350]] between Poole and Chippenham.\n\nDue to its hilltop location, Shaftesbury has never had a railway connection. In 1859 the [[Salisbury and Yeovil Railway]] (now the [[West of England line]]), running along the [[Vale of Wardour]], opened a [[Semley railway station|station at Semley]], approximately {{convert|2+1/2|mi|0}} north of Shaftesbury, to serve the town. When the station closed in 1966, [[Gillingham (Dorset) railway station|Gillingham station]] became the main railhead for Shaftesbury.\n\n==Sport and leisure==\n\nShaftesbury has a [[non-League football]] club, [[Shaftesbury F.C.]], who play at Cockrams.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.s299639758.websitehome.co.uk/shaftesbury.html# |title=Shaftesbury |publisher=S299639758.websitehome.co.uk |date= |accessdate=8 February 2013 }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Community facilities==\n\nShaftesbury has a community hospital and a library. Westminster Memorial Hospital on Abbey Walk provides a range of services, including minor surgery and several specialist clinics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dorsethealthcare.nhs.uk/services/community-hospitals/westminster-memorial-hospital.htm |title=Westminster Memorial Hospital |publisher=Dorset HealthCare University NHS Foundation Trust |accessdate=31 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150130065356/http://www.dorsethealthcare.nhs.uk/services/community-hospitals/westminster-memorial-hospital.htm |archivedate=30 January 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The library on Bell Street lends films and music as well as books, and provides free internet access.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://community.shaftesburydorset.com/library/ |title=Library |publisher=shaftesburydorset.com |accessdate=31 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150914192325/http://community.shaftesburydorset.com/library/ |archive-date=14 September 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n\nKing of England, Denmark, and Norway, [[Cnut the Great]], died here on 12 November 1035\n\nActor [[Robert Newton]], best known for his portrayals of [[Long John Silver]] and [[Bill Sikes]] in the 1948 [[David Lean]] film [[Oliver Twist (1948 film)|Oliver Twist]] was born here.\n\nArchitect [[Richard Upjohn]], famous for his Gothic Revival churches in the United States, including [[Trinity Church (Manhattan)|Trinity Church]] in [[New York City|New York]], was also born in Shaftesbury.\n\n==See also==\n* [[St Mary's School, Shaftesbury]]\n* [[Shaftesbury School]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===General references===\n* {{cite book |title=Dorset |author=J. H. Bettey |series=City & County Histories |year=1974 |publisher=David & Charles |ISBN=0-7153-6371-9}}\n* Pitt-Rivers, Michael, 1979.  ''Dorset''. London: Faber & Faber.\n* The 1985 AA illustrated guide to the country towns and villages of Britain.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.shaftesbury-tc.gov.uk/ Shaftesbury Town Council]\n* {{curlie|/Regional/Europe/United_Kingdom/England/Dorset/Shaftesbury}}\n{{commons category|Shaftesbury}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Shaftesbury}}\n{{Dorset}}\n{{North Dorset}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Shaftesbury| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Dorset]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the town in Dorset, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n| official_name= Shaftesbury\n| static_image_name= High Street, Shaftesbury - geograph.org.uk - 1440129.jpg\n| static_image_caption= High Street\n| map_type= Dorset\n| coordinates= {{coord|51.0059|-2.1969|display=inline,title}}\n| population= 7,314\n| population_ref= ([[2011 United Kingdom census|2011]])<ref name=ons>{{cite web |title=Area: Shaftesbury (Parish). Key Figures for 2011 Census: Key Statistics |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11128341&c=Shaftesbury&d=16&e=62&g=6418052&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&o=362&m=0&r=1&s=1433061124578&enc=1 |work=Neighbourhood Statistics |publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref>\n| os_grid_reference= ST861228\n| london_distance=\n| civil_parish= Shaftesbury\n| unitary_england= [[Dorset (unitary authority)|Dorset]]\n| lieutenancy_england= [[Dorset]]\n| region= South West England\n| country= England\n| post_town= SHAFTESBURY\n| postcode_area= SP\n| postcode_district= SP7\n| dial_code= 01747\n| constituency_westminster= [[North Dorset (constituency)|North Dorset]]\n}}\n[[File:Milestone, Blandford Forum - geograph.org.uk - 1714569.jpg|thumb|upright|Old milestone in [[Blandford Forum]] showing use of the name Shaston for Shaftesbury]]\n\n'''Shaftesbury''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0283|\u0251\u02d0|f|t|s|b|\u0259r|i|,_|\u02c8|\u0283|\u00e6|f|t|s|-}}) is a town and [[civil parish]] in [[Dorset]], England. It is situated on the [[A30 road]], {{convert|20|miles|km|0}} west of [[Salisbury, Wiltshire|Salisbury]], near to the border with [[Wiltshire]]. It is the only significant hilltop settlement in Dorset, being built about {{convert|215|m|ft}} [[Above mean sea level|above sea level]] on a [[greensand]] hill on the edge of [[Cranborne Chase]]. Shaftesbury also refers to a former carehome, located in Exeter, prominent during the 20th and early 21st centuries.  \n\nThe town looks over the [[Blackmore Vale]], part of the [[River Stour, Dorset|River Stour]] basin. From different viewpoints, it is possible to see at least as far as [[Glastonbury Tor]] to the northwest.\n\nShaftesbury is the site of the former [[Shaftesbury Abbey]], which was founded in 888 by [[Alfred the Great|King Alfred]] and became one of the richest religious establishments in the country, before being destroyed in the [[Dissolution of the Monasteries|Dissolution]] in 1539. Adjacent to the abbey site is [[Gold Hill, Shaftesbury|Gold Hill]], a steep [[Cobblestone|cobbled]] street used in the 1970s as the setting for [[Ridley Scott]]{{'}}s television advertisement for [[Hovis]] bread.\n\nIn the [[2011 United Kingdom census|2011 Census]] the town's civil parish had a population of 7,314.\n\n==Toponymy==\nShaftesbury has acquired a number of names throughout its history. Writing in 1906, [[Sir Frederick Treves, 1st Baronet|Sir Frederick Treves]] referred to four of these names from Celtic, Latin and English traditions in his book ''Highways & Byways in Dorset'':\n{{quote|text=The city has had many names. It was, in the beginning, Caer Palladour. By the time of the Domesday Book it was Sceptesberie. It then, with all the affectation of a lady in an eighteenth-century lyric, called itself Sophonia. Lastly it became Shaston, and so the people call it to this day, while all the milestones around concern themselves only with recording the distances to \"Shaston\".|sign=Sir Frederick Treves|source=Highways & Byways in Dorset (1906)}}\n\nThe original [[Common Brittonic|Celtic]] name is first recorded in [[Medieval Welsh literature]] as ''Caer Vynnydd y Paladr'' (The Mountain Fort/City of the Spears)<ref>[[Brut y Brenhinedd]] (mid 13th century document largely regarded as an accurate account of the early history of the Britons)</ref> and [[Thomas Gale]] records the name as ''Caer Palladour'' in his work of 1709.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Gale |first1=Thomas |title=Antonini iter Britanniarum commentariis illustratum |date=1709 |location=London |page=132 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cm5bAAAAQAAJ&pg=PT1&lpg=PT1&dq=Caer+Palladour&source=bl&ots=tfI8Uof9hJ&sig=ACfU3U1sJLg9Iw2hbSX8MY6EIj-_kPAeyw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjWkvLOko7oAhWSX8AKHXp8AxgQ6AEwCXoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q&f=false |language=Latin}}</ref> Though \"Palladour\" was described by one 19th-century directory as \"mere invention\", it has continued to be used as a poetic and alternative name for the town.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SZYIAAAAQAAJ&pg=RA1-PA134&lpg=RA1-PA134&dq=sophonia+shaftesbury&source=bl&ots=oZXmxEnpRC&sig=3bVaZjF_K-1I33h0bTLFychYy1w&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-v2LUsXKL4TBhAf4xoDoDQ&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=sophonia%20shaftesbury&f=false|title=Topographical and Statistical Description of the County of Dorset|last=Cooke|first=George Alexander|year=|publisher=|page=134|accessdate=20 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe English name was recorded in the [[Domesday Book]] as Sceptesberie,<ref>{{cite web|title=The Domesday Book Online. Dorset S-Z|publisher=domesdaybook.co.uk|year=1999\u20132013|accessdate=19 November 2013|url=http://www.domesdaybook.co.uk/dorset3.html}}</ref> and the use of \"Shaston\" ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0283|\u00e6|s|t|\u0259n}}) was recorded in 1831 in Samuel Lewis's ''A Topographical Dictionary of England''<ref name=\"Lewis1831\">{{cite book|last=Lewis|first=Samuel |title=A Topographical Dictionary of England|url=https://archive.org/details/atopographicald00lewigoog|accessdate=17 December 2012|year=1831|publisher=S. Lewis|page=[https://archive.org/details/atopographicald00lewigoog/page/n67 61]}}</ref> and in 1840 in ''The parliamentary gazetteer of England and Wales''.<ref name=\"gazetteer1840\">{{cite book|author=England|title=The parliamentary gazetteer of England and Wales|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uNgHAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA94|accessdate=17 December 2012|year=1840|page=94}}</ref>\n\n[[Thomas Hardy]] used both \"Shaston\" and \"Palladour\" to refer to the town in the fictional [[Thomas Hardy's Wessex|Wessex]] of his novels such as ''[[Jude the Obscure]]''<ref>{{cite book|last=Ross|first=Alexander|title=The Imprint of the Picturesque on Nineteenth-century British Fiction|url=https://archive.org/details/imprintofpicture0000ross|url-access=registration|quote=palladour tess.|accessdate=19 November 2013|publisher=Wilfrid Laurier Univ. Press|page=[https://archive.org/details/imprintofpicture0000ross/page/136 136]|year=1986}}</ref>\n\nShaftesbury house also has a variety of terms linked to it, most prominently the 'shaftening', a generic term applied to activities that take place within the house. \n==History==\nThere is no substantive evidence that Shaftesbury was the \"Caer Palladur\" (or \"Caer Palladwr\") of Celtic and Roman times, and instead the town's recorded history dates from [[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo-Saxon times]].<ref>{{cite book|title=North Dorset District Official Guide|publisher=Home Publishing Company Ltd|pages=23\u201324|author=North Dorset District Council|year=c. 1983}}</ref> By the early 8th century there was an important minster church here,<ref name=\"Bettey, pp 62-63\">Bettey, pp 62-63</ref> and in 880 [[Alfred the Great]] founded a [[burgh]] (fortified settlement) here as a defence in the struggle with the [[Danes (Germanic tribe)|Danish]] invaders.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}} The burgh is recorded in the early-10th-century [[Burghal Hidage]] as one of only three that existed in the county (the others being at [[Wareham, Dorset|Wareham]] and 'Bredy' - which is probably [[Bridport]]).<ref name=\"Bettey, pp 62-63\"/>\n[[File:Ruins of Shaftesbury Abbey (geograph 3605823).jpg|thumb|left|The ruins of [[Shaftesbury Abbey]]]]\n\nIn 888 Alfred founded [[Shaftesbury Abbey]], a [[Benedictine]] [[nunnery]] by the town's east gate, and appointed his daughter Ethelgifu as the first [[abbess]].<ref>Bettey, p30</ref> [[\u00c6thelstan]] founded two royal mints,<ref name=hyams>{{cite book |title=Dorset |first=John |last=Hyams |publisher=B. T. Batsford Ltd |year=1970 |page=197 |isbn=0-7134-0066-8}}</ref> which struck pennies bearing the town's name, and the abbey became the wealthiest Benedictine nunnery in England. On 20 February 981 the relics of St [[Edward the Martyr]], the teenage King of England, were transferred from Wareham and received at the abbey with great ceremony, thereafter turning Shaftesbury into a major site of pilgrimage for miracles of healing.\n\n[[Cnut the Great|King Canute]] died here in 1035, though he was buried at [[Winchester]].<ref name=hyams/> [[Edward the Confessor]] licensed a third mint for the town.<ref name=hyams/> By the time of the [[Norman conquest of England|Norman conquest]] in 1066 Shaftesbury had 257 houses, though many were destroyed in the ensuing years of conflict, and by the time the [[Domesday Book]] was compiled twenty years later, there were only 177 houses remaining, though this still meant that Shaftesbury was the largest town in Dorset at that time.<ref>Bettey, p63</ref> Around this time the town's ownership was equally shared between king and abbey.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}} In the [[The Anarchy|first English civil war]] (1135-1154) between [[Empress Matilda]] and [[Stephen, King of England|King Stephen]], an [[adulterine castle]] or fortified house was built on a small [[promontory]] at the western edge of the hill on which the old town was built. The site on Castle Hill, also known locally as Boltbury, is now under grass and is a [[scheduled monument]].<ref name=gatehouse>{{cite web |url=http://www.gatehouse-gazetteer.info/English%20sites/956.html |title=Shaftesbury Castle Hill |publisher=gatehouse-gazetteer |date=29 May 2015 |accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1240 Cardinal Otto ([[Oddone di Monferrato]]), legate to the [[Apostolic See]] of [[Pope Gregory IX]] visited the abbey and confirmed a charter of 1191, the first entered in the Glastonbury chartulary. During the [[Middle Ages]] the abbey was the central focus of the town; the abbey's great wealth was acknowledged in a popular saying at the time, which stated that \"If the abbot of Glastonbury could marry the abbess of Shaftesbury their heir would hold more land than the king of England\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/dorset/vol2/pp73-79 |title='House of Benedictine nuns: The abbey of Shaftesbury', in A History of the County of Dorset: Volume 2, ed. William Page (London, 1908), pp. 73-79 |publisher=University of London |accessdate=13 May 2015 |work=British History Online}}</ref> In 1260 a charter to hold a market was granted. By 1340 the mayor had become a recognised figure, sworn in by the steward of the abbess. In 1392 [[Richard II of England|Richard II]] confirmed a grant of two markets on different days. Edwardstow, Shaftesbury's oldest surviving building, was built on Bimport at some time between 1400 and 1539. Also in this period a medieval farm owned by the Abbess of Shaftesbury was established, on a site now occupied by the Tesco supermarket car park.\n[[File:Edwardstowe, Shaftesbury - geograph.org.uk - 224159.jpg|thumb|Edwardstow]]\n\nIn 1539, the last Abbess of Shaftesbury, Elizabeth Zouche, signed a deed of surrender, the (by then extremely wealthy) abbey was demolished, and its lands sold, leading to a temporary decline in the town. [[Thomas Arundell of Wardour Castle|Sir Thomas Arundell]] purchased the abbey and much of the town in 1540, but when he was later exiled for treason his lands were forfeit, and the lands passed to Pembroke then [[Anthony Ashley-Cooper, 7th Earl of Shaftesbury]], and finally to the Grosvenors.\n\nShaftesbury was a parliamentary constituency returning two members from 1296 to the [[Reform Act 1832|Reform Act of 1832]], when it was reduced to one, and in 1884 the separate constituency was abolished.\n\nIn ''Survey of Dorsetshire'', written in about 1630 by Thomas Gerard of the Dorset village of [[Trent, Dorset|Trent]], Shaftesbury is described as a \"faire Thorough Faire, much frequented by Travellers to and from London\".<ref>Bettey, p129</ref>\n\nThe town was broadly Parliamentarian in the [[English Civil War|Civil War]], but was in Royalist hands. [[Wardour Castle]] fell to Parliamentary forces in 1643; Parliamentary forces surrounded the town in August 1645, when it was a centre of local [[clubmen]] activity. The clubmen were arrested and sent to trial in [[Sherborne]]. Shaftesbury took no part in the [[Monmouth Rebellion]] of 1685.\n\nIn the 17th century the cloth industry formed part of Shaftesbury's economy, though much of the actual production took place as a [[cottage industry]] in the surrounding area. In the 18th century the town produced a coarse white woollen cloth called 'swanskin', that was used by fishermen of [[Newfoundland]] and for uniforms.<ref>Bettey, pp 75-76</ref> [[Dorset button|Buttonmaking]] also became important around this time, though with the later advent of [[Industrial Revolution|industrialisation]] this subsequently declined, resulting in unemployment, starvation and emigration, with 350 families leaving for [[Canada]].<ref name=loaf>{{cite web|url=http://www.dorsetlife.co.uk/2009/08/more-to-it-than-a-brown-loaf/|title=More to it than a brown loaf|date=August 2009|author=Tony Burton-Page|publisher=Dorset Life|accessdate=20 November 2013}}</ref> [[Malting]] and [[brewing]] were also significant in the 17th and 18th centuries, and like other Dorset towns such as [[Dorchester, Dorset|Dorchester]] and [[Blandford Forum]], Shaftesbury became known for its beer.<ref name=Bettey81>Bettey, p81</ref>\n\nIn the 18th century the [[Toll road|turnpike road]]s which met at Shaftesbury ensured that the town had a good coaching trade.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}} The railways however bypassed the town, which had consequences for Shaftesbury's economy; during the 19th century the town's brewing industry was reduced to serving only local markets, as towns elsewhere in the country could transport their produce more cheaply.<ref name=Bettey81/> During the 19th century the population of the town grew little.<ref>Bettey, pp 72-73</ref>\n\n[[File:Shaftesbury Town Hall - geograph.org.uk - 1436981.jpg|thumb|left|St Peter's Church and the town hall]]\nThe town hall was built in 1827 by Earl Grosvenor after the guildhall was pulled down to widen High Street. It has been designated by [[English Heritage]] as a grade II listed building.<ref>{{cite web | title=The Town Hall | work=historicengland.org.uk | url=https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1108741 | accessdate=29 December 2007}}</ref> The town hall is next to the 15th-century St Peter's Church.<ref>{{cite web | title=Church of St Peter | work=historicengland.org.uk | url=https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1292132 | accessdate=29 December 2007}}</ref> The [[Westminster Memorial Hospital]] was constructed on Bimport in the mid-19th century with a legacy from the wife of the [[Richard Grosvenor, 2nd Marquess of Westminster|Duke of Westminster]].<ref>''The Cottage Hospitals 1859-1990''. Dr Meyrick Emrys-Roberts, 1991. Tern Publications, Motcombe, Dorset. {{ISBN|0951713604}}</ref>\n\nIn 1918 Lord Stalbridge sold a large portion of the town, which was purchased by a syndicate and auctioned piece by piece over three days.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dorsetlife.co.uk/2008/03/the-fall-of-the-house-of-stalbridge/ |title=The fall of the House of Stalbridge |publisher=Dorset Life Magazine |date=March 2008 |author=Alan J Miller |accessdate=19 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nMost of Shaftesbury's buildings date from no earlier than the 18th century, as the [[Saxons|Saxon]] and most of the medieval buildings have not survived.\n\nDuring the 1950s and onwards a large amount of low-cost housing has been established around the outskirts of Shaftesbury{{Citation needed|date=December 2012}}.\nAt present, the house continues to be occupied by 9 'shafters'. \n\n==Governance==\nIn the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|United Kingdom national parliament]], Shaftesbury is in the [[North Dorset (UK Parliament constituency)|North Dorset parliamentary constituency]] which is currently [[Member of Parliament|represented]] by [[Simon Hoare]] of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative party]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000839 |title=Dorset North Parliamentary constituency |work=Election 2015 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=10 May 2015}}</ref> At the top tier of [[local government]] Shaftesbury is governed by [[Dorset County Council]], the main responsibilities of which include schools and other education, highways, planning, waste, public transport, social care, countryside and heritage, public health, libraries, museums and the arts, archives, trading standards and planning for emergencies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dorsetforyou.com/article/387750/Dorset-County-Council---budget-books |title=The Budget Book 2014 - 2015 (pdf) |publisher=Dorset County Council |work=dorsetforyou.com |accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref> At the middle tier of local government Shaftesbury is governed by North Dorset District Council. Since 2006 North Dorset District Council has reduced its direct service provision via a system of decentralised community partnerships with local organisations such as town councils.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.reform.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/North_Dorset_District_Council.pdf |title=North Dorset District Council |work=reform.uk |accessdate=16 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925133402/http://www.reform.uk/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/North_Dorset_District_Council.pdf |archive-date=25 September 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> North Dorset District Council is also in a 'tri-council' partnership with two other district-level councils in Dorset, West Dorset District Council and Weymouth and Portland Borough Council; the aim of the partnership is to reduce costs of management and buildings.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-dorset-31542441 |title=North Dorset approves 'tri-council' partnership |publisher=BBC |date=19 February 2015 |accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref> At the bottom tier of local government Shaftesbury is governed by Shaftesbury Town Council,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://towncouncil.shaftesburydorset.com/ |title=Welcome to Shaftesbury Town Council |publisher=Shaftesbury Town Council |work=shaftesburydorset.com |accessdate=6 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150405023327/http://towncouncil.shaftesburydorset.com/ |archive-date=5 April 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> which has responsibilities that include open spaces and recreational facilities, allotments, litter, street markets, public conveniences, grants to voluntary organisations, cemetery provision, bus shelters, crime prevention initiatives, civic events and the town hall, planning (as a consultee) and the war memorial.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shaftesburytowncouncil.co.uk/about/what-we-do |title=What We Do |publisher=Shaftesbury Town Council |accessdate=16 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150802205252/http://www.shaftesburytowncouncil.co.uk/about/what-we-do |archivedate=2 August 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFor electoral purposes Shaftesbury is divided into two [[Wards and electoral divisions of the United Kingdom|electoral wards]]: Shaftesbury West and Shaftesbury East. In national parliamentary elections these are joined with 25 other wards that together elect the Member of Parliament for the North Dorset constituency.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.electoralcalculus.co.uk/cgi-bin/seatdetails.pl?seat=Dorset%20North |title=Dorset North: Seat, Ward and Prediction Details |publisher=electoralcalculus.co.uk |accessdate=16 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925122148/http://www.electoralcalculus.co.uk/cgi-bin/seatdetails.pl?seat=Dorset%20North |archivedate=25 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In county council elections the two wards together form Shaftesbury electoral division, one of 42 divisions that each elect councillors to Dorset County Council.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dorsetforyou.com/390881 |title=Electoral division profiles 2013 |publisher=Dorset County Council |work=dorsetforyou.com |date= |accessdate=6 May 2015}}</ref> The county council has 45 councillors (three divisions elect two councillors each)<ref name=committee>{{cite web |url=http://www1.dorsetforyou.com/Council/COMMIS2013.nsf/MEM?OpenView&Count=1000 |title=Committee Information |publisher=Dorset County Council |work=dorsetforyou.com |accessdate=16 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925095104/http://www1.dorsetforyou.com/Council/COMMIS2013.nsf/MEM?OpenView&Count=1000 |archivedate=25 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and the Conservative Party has overall control,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dorsetforyou.com/councillors/county |title=Dorset county councillors |publisher=Dorset County Council |work=dorsetforyou.com |date=17 January 2015 |accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref> though the councillor representing Shaftesbury is a [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]].<ref name=committee/> In district council elections the two wards, together with seventeen other wards within the [[North Dorset|North Dorset District]], elect councillors to North Dorset District Council; the two Shaftesbury wards each elect two councillors<ref name=legislation>{{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukdsi/2014/9780111115473?view=plain |title=The North Dorset (Electoral Changes) Order 2014 |publisher= |work=legislation.gov.uk |accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref> out of a total of 33. The Conservative Party has overall control of the district council, though of the four councillors that represent Shaftesbury, one is a Liberal Democrat and one is an [[Independent politician|independent]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dorsetforyou.com/councillors/north |title=North Dorset district councillors |publisher=Dorset County Council |work=dorsetforyou.com |date=5 September 2014 |accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref> In town council elections Shaftesbury's two wards each elect six councillors to Shaftesbury Town Council.<ref name=legislation/> The mayor of Shaftesbury for 2016-17 is Dr Richard Tippins.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shaftesburytowncouncil.co.uk/who-we-are |title=Who We Are |publisher=Shaftesbury Town Council |accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Viewpoint, Park Walk,Shaftesbury - geograph.org.uk - 1436844.jpg|thumb|Looking south from the town towards [[Melbury Hill]], from Park Walk]]\n\n==Geography==\nThe old centre of Shaftesbury is sited on a westward-pointing [[promontory]] of high ground in northeast Dorset, on the [[escarpment|scarp edge]] of a range of hills that extend south and east into [[Cranborne Chase]] and neighbouring [[Wiltshire]].<ref name=Survey2013>Ordnance Survey (2013), 1:25,000 Explorer Map, Sheet 118 (Shaftesbury and Cranborne Chase), {{ISBN|978-0-319-24123-3}}</ref><ref>John Bartholomew & Son Ltd (1980), 1:100,000 National Map Series, Sheet 4 (Dorset), {{ISBN|0-7028-0327-8}}</ref> The town's built-up area also extends down the promontory slopes to lower ground at St James, Alcester and Enmore Green, and eastwards across the [[Drainage divide|watershed]] towards the hill's dip slope.<ref name=Survey2013/> Shaftesbury's altitude is between about {{convert|165|m|ft}} at the lowest streets below the promontory, to about {{convert|235|m|ft}} at Wincombe Business Park on the hilltop in the north, with the promontory and town centre being at about {{convert|215|m|ft}}.<ref name=Survey2013/> Below the town to the west is the [[Blackmore Vale]], which undulates between about {{convert|60|m|ft}} and {{convert|110|m|ft}}.<ref>Ornance Survey (2005), 1:50,000 Landranger Map, Sheet 183 (Yeovil & Frome), {{ISBN|978-0-319-22861-6}}</ref> About {{convert|2|miles|km|0}} to the west of the town and within the Blackmore Vale is the conical mound of [[Duncliffe Hill]], visible for miles and home to Duncliffe Wood and a nature reserve. The countryside east of the town is part of the [[Cranborne Chase and West Wiltshire Downs]] [[Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ccwwdaonb.org.uk/docs/General_MapSW.pdf |title=Cranborne Chase & West Wiltshire Downs Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty |publisher=ccwwdaonb.org.uk |accessdate=27 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130808041911/http://ccwwdaonb.org.uk/docs/General_MapSW.pdf |archivedate=8 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nGeologically, Shaftesbury's hill mostly comprises [[Greensand|Upper Greensand]], which is overlain by Lower [[Chalk]] in the east. These date from the [[Cretaceous]], with the greensand having been formed in the [[Albian]] and early [[Cenomanian]], and the chalk also in the Cenomanian. The greensand is composed of three [[Bed (geology)|beds]]: the oldest and lowest is a layer of Cann Sand, which is found in the lower parts of the town, such as St James and Alcester, that are below the promontory; above this is a layer of Shaftesbury Sandstone, which generally forms the steepest slopes around the promontory, and on top of this is a layer of Boyne Hollow Chert, which is found on top of the hill and on which most of the town is built. Below the Cann Sand, on the lower slopes of the hill to the north, west and south of the town, are extensive landslip deposits.<ref>British Geological Survey (1994), 1:50,000 Series England and Wales Sheet 313, Shaftesbury Solid and Drift Geology, {{ISBN|0-7518-2823-8}}</ref>\n[[File:High Street ,Shaftesbury, Dorset - geograph.org.uk - 411160.jpg|thumb|left|Businesses on High Street]]\n\n==Economy==\nIn 2012 there were 3,400 people employed in Shaftesbury, 65% of whom were working full-time and 35% part-time.<ref name=profile>{{cite web|url=https://www.dorsetforyou.com/article/343604/Shaftesbury-town-profile |title=Shaftesbury town profile |publisher=Dorset County Council / archive.org |work=dorsetforyou.com |date=3 November 2014 |accessdate=16 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710020114/https://www.dorsetforyou.com/article/343604/Shaftesbury-town-profile |archivedate=10 July 2015 }}</ref> Excluding agriculture, the most important employment sectors were public administration, education and health (31% of non-agricultural employment), production and construction (29%), and distribution, accommodation and food (26%).<ref name=profile/> Significant employers include [[Dorset County Council]], [[Pork Farms]], [[Guys Marsh (HM Prison)|Guys Marsh Prison]], [[Royal Mail]], [[Somerfield]], [[Tesco]], [[Port Regis School]], Wessex Electricals, Stalbridge Linen Services, Blackmore Press and Dorset Chilled Foods.<ref name=profile/> There are two industrial estates in the town: Longmead Industrial Estate, covering {{convert|7.7|ha|acre}}, and Wincombe Business Park, covering {{convert|6.5|ha|acre}}.<ref name=profile/>\n\nIn 2005 there were 75 shops in the town, with a total floorspace of {{convert|78000|sqft|sqm}}. The retail catchment area for major food shopping extends about {{convert|4.5|mi|km}} in all directions. National retail [[chain store|chains]] with a presence in the town include [[the Body Shop]], [[Boots UK|Boots]], Somerfield, [[Superdrug]], Tesco and [[WHSmith]].<ref name=profile/>\n\nA site has been identified for a projected parkway station on the [[West of England]] main railway line. It would be situated to the north of the town, beneath the A350 road, and a bus service would connect it with the town.{{Citation needed|date=April 2013}} Currently the nearest railway station is located in neighbouring [[Gillingham, Dorset|Gillingham]].\n\n==Demography==\nIn the [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 census]] Shaftesbury's civil parish had 3,493 dwellings,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=11128341&c=Shaftesbury&d=16&e=62&g=6418052&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&o=362&m=0&r=1&s=1433061469234&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2481 |title=Area: Shaftesbury (Parish). Dwellings, Household Spaces and Accommodation Type, 2011 (KS401EW)|publisher=Office for National Statistics |work=Neighbourhood Statistics |accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> 3,235 households and a population of 7,314.<ref name=ons/> The average age of inhabitants was 43, compared to 39.3 for England as a whole. 22.1% of inhabitants were age 65 or older, compared to 16.4% for England as a whole.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=11128341&c=Shaftesbury&d=16&e=62&g=6418052&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1431763097508&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2474 |title=Area: Shaftesbury (Parish). Age Structure, 2011 (KS102EW) |publisher=Office for National Statistics |work=Neighbourhood Statistics |accessdate=16 May 2015}}</ref> 92% of Shaftesbury's residents were born in the United Kingdom, compared to 86.2% for England as a whole.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=11128341&c=Shaftesbury&d=16&e=62&g=6418052&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1433060431375&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2478 |title=Area: Shaftesbury (Parish). Country of Birth, 2011 (KS204EW) |publisher=Office for National Statistics |work=Neighbourhood Statistics |accessdate=31 May 2015}}</ref> Previous census figures for the total population of the civil parish are shown in the table below:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:800px;\"\n! colspan= \"15\" style=\"background:; color:\" | <span style=\"margin-left: 80px; color: \">Census Population of Shaftesbury Parish 1921\u20142001 <small>(except 1941)</small></span>\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background:; color: height:15px;\"| Census\n! style=\"background:;\"| 1921\n! style=\"background:;\"| 1931\n! style=\"background:;\"| 1951\n! style=\"background:;\"| 1961\n! style=\"background:;\"| 1971\n! style=\"background:;\"| 1981\n! style=\"background:;\"| 1991\n! style=\"background:;\"| 2001\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background:; color: height:15px;\"|Population\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2;\"| *1,812\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2;\"| *2,819\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2;\"| *3,303\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2;\"| 3,372\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2;\"| 3,980\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2;\"| 3,940\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2;\"| 6,180\n| style=\"background:#F2F2F2;\"| 6,680\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| colspan=\"15\" style=\"background:#F2F2F2; color: text-align:center;\"| <small>Asterisks (*) indicate a boundary change<br>Source:Dorset County Council<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dorsetforyou.com/article/345043/Parishes-M-Z-1921-2001-Census-Years |title=Parishes (M-Z), 1921-2001 Census Years |publisher=Dorset County Council |work=dorsetforyou.com |accessdate=23 May 2015 |date=27 May 2014}}</ref>\n</small>\n|}\n\n==Culture, art and media==\n[[File:Snowdrop Festival, Shaftesbury (12673314263).jpg|thumb|right|Shaftesbury Snowdrops]]\nShaftesbury Arts Centre was established in 1957 and stages a variety of exhibitions, performances, workshops and training courses. It is based in the old covered market in the town centre and is a charitable company that is run wholly by its volunteer members.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shaftesburyartscentre.org.uk/about-us |title=About Us |publisher=Shaftesbury Arts Centre |accessdate=30 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511002716/http://www.shaftesburyartscentre.org.uk/about-us |archivedate=11 May 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nShaftesbury has two museums: Gold Hill Museum at the top of Gold Hill, and Shaftesbury Abbey Museum in the abbey grounds.<ref name=loaf/><ref name=abbeymuseum>{{cite web |url=http://shaftesburyabbey.org.uk/ |title=Shaftesbury Abbey Museum & Gardens |publisher=Shaftesbury Abbey Museum & Gardens |accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref> Gold Hill Museum was founded in 1946 and displays many artefacts that relate to the history of Shaftesbury and the surrounding area, including Dorset's oldest fire engine, dating from 1744.<ref name=loaf/> Shaftesbury Abbey Museum tells the story of the abbey and also has a herb garden and medieval orchard.<ref name=abbeymuseum/>\n\nShaftesbury Snowdrops is a Diamond Jubilee Community Legacy with the aim of creating a series of free and accessible [[Galanthus nivalis|snowdrop]] walks by planting snowdrops within the publicly open spaces and along the pathways throughout the town. The project was started in the winter of 2012 with the planting of 60,000 bulbs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hundreds of Shaftesbury snowdrops planted after Diamond Jubilee|url=http://www.blackmorevale.co.uk/Hundreds-Shaftesbury-snowdrops-planted-Diamond/story-17587450-detail/story.html|website=www.blackmorevale.co.uk|publisher=Blackmore Vale Magazine|accessdate=22 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122152504/http://www.blackmorevale.co.uk/Hundreds-Shaftesbury-snowdrops-planted-Diamond/story-17587450-detail/story.html|archivedate=22 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Since 2013 there has been an annual Snowdrop Festival to encourage tourists to see the snowdrops in flower.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shaftesbury celebrates the snowdrop|url=http://www.blackmorevale.co.uk/Shaftesbury-celebrates-snowdrop/story-18090175-detail/story.html|website=www.blackmorevale.co.uk|publisher=Blackmore Vale Magazine|accessdate=22 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122150948/http://www.blackmorevale.co.uk/Shaftesbury-celebrates-snowdrop/story-18090175-detail/story.html|archivedate=22 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Highlights of the festival include the Snowdrop Art Exhibition<ref>{{cite web|title=Shaftesbury Snowdrop Festival Art Exhibition 2013|url=http://www.blackmorevale.co.uk/pictures/PHOTOS-Shaftesbury-Snowdrop-Festival-Art/pictures-18182409-detail/pictures.html|website=www.blackmorevale.co.uk|publisher=Blackmore Vale Magazine|accessdate=22 January 2015}}</ref> and the Snowdrop Lantern Parade.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shaftesbury Snowdrop Festival - starts 15th Feb|url=http://www.blackmorevale.co.uk/pictures/PHOTOS-Shaftesbury-Snowdrop-Festival-starts-15th/pictures-20519657-detail/pictures.html|website=www.blackmorevale.co.uk|publisher=Blackmore Vale Magazine|accessdate=22 January 2015}}</ref> In 2014 Shaftesbury Snowdrops started a heritage collection of rare and unusual snowdrops.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shaftesbury Snowdrops Heritage Collection launched|url=http://www.blackmorevale.co.uk/PHOTOS-Shaftesbury-Snowdrops-Heritage-Collection/story-20643190-detail/story.html|website=www.blackmorevale.co.uk|publisher=Blackmore Vale Magazine|accessdate=22 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122125355/http://www.blackmorevale.co.uk/PHOTOS-Shaftesbury-Snowdrops-Heritage-Collection/story-20643190-detail/story.html|archivedate=22 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  These are held in trust for the people of Shaftesbury and displayed in Shaftesbury Abbey during the annual Snowdrop Festival. The collection is being built through sponsorship and donations.\n\nGold Hill Fair usually occurs in the first weekend of July and has food stalls, arts stalls and local music that can be found in the abbey ruins.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://shaftesburyrotaryclub.org/upcoming-events/gold-hill-fair/|title=Gold Hill Fair - Shaftesbury Rotary Club|work=Shaftesbury Rotary Club|access-date=2017-05-12|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n[[File:Gold Hill, Shaftsbury, Dorset, England.JPG|thumb|Steep, [[cobblestones|cobbled]] Gold Hill, with a [[buttress]]ed wall to the right, a [[scheduled monument]] on the edge of Shaftesbury Abbey [[religious precinct|precinct]]<ref>[https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1004559 Abbey precinct wall on Gold Hill], [[Historic England]], 17 September 2019. Retrieved 17 September 2019</ref>]]\n\n===Representations===\n[[Thomas Hardy]] used the names ''Shaston'' or ''Palladour'' to describe Shaftesbury in the fictional [[Thomas Hardy's Wessex|Wessex]] of his novels. In ''[[Jude the Obscure]]'' he described the loss of the town's former architectural glories, principally the abbey:\n\n''\"Vague imaginings of its castle, its three mints, its magnificent apsidal abbey, the chief glory of south Wessex, its twelve churches, its shrines, chantries, hospitals, its gabled freestone mansions\u2014all now ruthlessly swept away\u2014throw the visitor, even against his will, into a pensive melancholy, which the stimulating atmosphere and limitless landscape around him can scarcely dispel.\"''<ref>In: Hardy, Thomas (1895). ''[[Jude the Obscure]]'', [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=oTIgSfMC3akC&lpg=PA356&dq=%22Shaston%2C%20the%20ancient%22&pg=PA356#v=onepage&q=%22Shaston,%20the%20ancient%22&f=false part fourth, chapter I]. Retrieved 17 December 2011.</ref>\n\nIn the 1970s [[Ridley Scott]] used [[Gold Hill, Shaftesbury|Gold Hill]], a steep cobbled street in the town, as the setting for a television advertisement for [[Hovis]] bread, in which a bread delivery boy is seen pushing his bicycle up the street before freewheeling back down. The advertisement made the street nationally famous.<ref name=loaf/>\n\n==Transport==\n{{expand section|date=June 2018}}\nShaftesbury is served by the [[A30 road (Great Britain)|A30]] between London and Exeter, and the [[A350 road (Great Britain)|A350]] between Poole and Chippenham.\n\nDue to its hilltop location, Shaftesbury has never had a railway connection. In 1859 the [[Salisbury and Yeovil Railway]] (now the [[West of England line]]), running along the [[Vale of Wardour]], opened a [[Semley railway station|station at Semley]], approximately {{convert|2+1/2|mi|0}} north of Shaftesbury, to serve the town. When the station closed in 1966, [[Gillingham (Dorset) railway station|Gillingham station]] became the main railhead for Shaftesbury.\n\n==Sport and leisure==\n\nShaftesbury has a [[non-League football]] club, [[Shaftesbury F.C.]], who play at Cockrams.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.s299639758.websitehome.co.uk/shaftesbury.html# |title=Shaftesbury |publisher=S299639758.websitehome.co.uk |date= |accessdate=8 February 2013 }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Community facilities==\n\nShaftesbury has a community hospital and a library. Westminster Memorial Hospital on Abbey Walk provides a range of services, including minor surgery and several specialist clinics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dorsethealthcare.nhs.uk/services/community-hospitals/westminster-memorial-hospital.htm |title=Westminster Memorial Hospital |publisher=Dorset HealthCare University NHS Foundation Trust |accessdate=31 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150130065356/http://www.dorsethealthcare.nhs.uk/services/community-hospitals/westminster-memorial-hospital.htm |archivedate=30 January 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The library on Bell Street lends films and music as well as books, and provides free internet access.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://community.shaftesburydorset.com/library/ |title=Library |publisher=shaftesburydorset.com |accessdate=31 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150914192325/http://community.shaftesburydorset.com/library/ |archive-date=14 September 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n\nKing of England, Denmark, and Norway, [[Cnut the Great]], died here on 12 November 1035\n\nActor [[Robert Newton]], best known for his portrayals of [[Long John Silver]] and [[Bill Sikes]] in the 1948 [[David Lean]] film [[Oliver Twist (1948 film)|Oliver Twist]] was born here.\n\nArchitect [[Richard Upjohn]], famous for his Gothic Revival churches in the United States, including [[Trinity Church (Manhattan)|Trinity Church]] in [[New York City|New York]], was also born in Shaftesbury.\n\n==See also==\n* [[St Mary's School, Shaftesbury]]\n* [[Shaftesbury School]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===General references===\n* {{cite book |title=Dorset |author=J. H. Bettey |series=City & County Histories |year=1974 |publisher=David & Charles |ISBN=0-7153-6371-9}}\n* Pitt-Rivers, Michael, 1979.  ''Dorset''. London: Faber & Faber.\n* The 1985 AA illustrated guide to the country towns and villages of Britain.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.shaftesbury-tc.gov.uk/ Shaftesbury Town Council]\n* {{curlie|/Regional/Europe/United_Kingdom/England/Dorset/Shaftesbury}}\n{{commons category|Shaftesbury}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Shaftesbury}}\n{{Dorset}}\n{{North Dorset}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Shaftesbury| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Dorset]]\n", "name_user": "Lillygilly", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "